00:00:00,240 --> 00:00:01,040
CHAPTER ONE

2
00:00:02,240 --> 00:00:03,200
Three Bodies
 

3
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,320
The man who was waiting on the shore looked like 
a farmer. He wore the right kind of clothes,  

4
00:00:12,320 --> 00:00:17,600
and his van, which was parked on the dirt road 
above the beach, was suitably covered in mud.

5
00:00:19,280 --> 00:00:24,880
It was midnight on the first Monday in October, 
and for the next thirty minutes he had to wait  

6
00:00:24,880 --> 00:00:33,120
there. He stared out to sea. He was alone, as 
he knew he would be; it was planned that way.  

7
00:00:34,560 --> 00:00:39,600
This beach was always empty at this time of 
night. No cars drove along the dirt road.

8
00:00:41,360 --> 00:00:46,160
The clouds were low and thick. It would be 
difficult to see the boat until it was close.  

9
00:00:47,120 --> 00:00:48,240
That was planned as well.

10
00:00:50,160 --> 00:00:54,720
After he had waited twenty minutes he heard 
the sound of a quiet engine from the water  

11
00:00:55,360 --> 00:00:59,680
and then saw a black rubber boat, 
low in the water, approach the shore.  

12
00:01:00,800 --> 00:01:04,160
The engine stopped when the boat was 
about thirty feet from the shore.  

13
00:01:05,600 --> 00:01:10,240
The farmer looked around. 
There were no people, no cars.

14
00:01:11,680 --> 00:01:14,720
He carefully put a cigarette in 
his mouth and started to smoke it.  

15
00:01:16,080 --> 00:01:21,920
A man's voice came from the boat on the 
water: 'What kind of cigarette is that?'

16
00:01:23,360 --> 00:01:25,840
'Lucky Strike,' the farmer answered.

17
00:01:26,960 --> 00:01:30,960
Satisfied, the man in the boat asked, 'Luke?'

18
00:01:32,880 --> 00:01:41,040
'Sam,' replied the farmer. The man in the 
boat was Khamel, not Sam, and Luke knew it.

19
00:01:42,640 --> 00:01:47,280
Luke had often heard of Khamel, but he 
was not sure that they had met before.  

20
00:01:48,480 --> 00:01:55,520
Khamel had many names and many faces, and 
he spoke several languages. He was the most  

21
00:01:55,520 --> 00:02:03,760
famous and most feared killer in the world. He 
was the best. At first, twenty years ago, he had  

22
00:02:03,760 --> 00:02:10,000
killed for political reasons, but now he would 
kill anyone, anywhere, if the money was right.

23
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:17,920
Luke was excited. Khamel was going to be 
working in America. He wondered who was  

24
00:02:17,920 --> 00:02:24,400
going to die. Whoever it was, the killing would 
be quick and clean, and there would be no clues.

25
00:02:26,560 --> 00:02:32,640
At dawn, the stolen van stopped at a hotel 
in Georgetown, part of Washington, DC, the  

26
00:02:32,640 --> 00:02:39,120
political capital of the United States of America. 
Khamel got out of the van without a word to Luke.  

27
00:02:39,840 --> 00:02:44,640
They had not spoken throughout the journey, and 
Luke had been careful not to look at Khamel.  

28
00:02:45,440 --> 00:02:49,840
He didn't want to die; he didn't want 
Khamel to think he could recognize him.

29
00:02:51,840 --> 00:02:56,320
The room in the hotel was ready, of 
course. The curtains were tightly closed.  

30
00:02:57,040 --> 00:03:02,320
The car keys were on the table. The 
gun was in a briefcase next to the bed.

31
00:03:03,760 --> 00:03:06,960
He had received three million 
dollars already for this job.  

32
00:03:07,920 --> 00:03:12,400
He would phone his bank in three hours to ask 
whether the next four million had arrived.  

33
00:03:13,920 --> 00:03:19,440
While he waited, he practised his English in 
front of the mirror. The job would be over by  

34
00:03:19,440 --> 00:03:24,160
midnight tonight, so another three million 
would reach his bank by midday tomorrow.  

35
00:03:25,200 --> 00:03:32,480
By then he would be in Paris. It was 
satisfactory. He allowed himself a short sleep.

36
00:03:34,280 --> 00:03:35,280
***

37
00:03:35,280 --> 00:03:43,360
The Supreme Court is the highest court in the USA. 
It consists of nine judges, who hear only the most  

38
00:03:43,360 --> 00:03:48,800
difficult cases in the country - those cases 
which might actually threaten the Constitution.  

39
00:03:50,560 --> 00:03:57,520
Judges are appointed to the Supreme Court by the 
government, so a Republican government will try to  

40
00:03:57,520 --> 00:04:03,680
get Republican judges appointed and a Democratic 
government will try to get Democrats appointed.  

41
00:04:05,200 --> 00:04:08,240
Judges become members of 
the Supreme Court for life.  

42
00:04:09,520 --> 00:04:14,880
They can retire if they want, but 
if not the job ends only with death.  

43
00:04:16,880 --> 00:04:24,800
Judge Rosenberg was so old that he found it hard 
to stay awake sometimes, even during trials. He  

44
00:04:24,800 --> 00:04:32,880
was a liberal, and proud of it. He defended the 
Indians, the homosexuals, the poor, the blacks,  

45
00:04:32,880 --> 00:04:42,080
the Mexicans and the Puerto Ricans. Some people 
loved him for it, but more people hated him.

46
00:04:42,080 --> 00:04:46,080
Throughout the summer there had been 
the usual number of messages threatening  

47
00:04:46,080 --> 00:04:52,560
death to the judges of the Supreme Court, and as 
usual Rosenberg had received more than the others.  

48
00:04:54,080 --> 00:04:58,160
The FBI had to behave as if the 
judges really were in danger,  

49
00:04:58,800 --> 00:05:03,280
although they were threatened year after year 
and it was very rare for anything to happen.  

50
00:05:04,400 --> 00:05:10,320
When it did, it was usually a single madman, whose 
daughter had died in a road accident or something.  

51
00:05:11,840 --> 00:05:17,520
The political groups made a lot of noise, but it 
was easier for them to bomb buildings than people,  

52
00:05:18,240 --> 00:05:23,840
and especially people who were as well 
guarded as the Supreme Court judges.

53
00:05:24,640 --> 00:05:32,160
Rosenberg refused to have FBI guards in his own 
home; he had lived to be ninety-one and was not  

54
00:05:32,160 --> 00:05:38,800
afraid of death. Judge Jensen had different 
reasons for not wanting guards in his house:  

55
00:05:39,840 --> 00:05:47,440
he wanted to be able to come and go as he pleased. 
Both of them allowed the guards to wait outside,  

56
00:05:47,440 --> 00:05:52,720
in cars or on foot, but they could enter 
the house only when they had permission.

57
00:05:55,520 --> 00:05:59,360
A little after ten at night, when 
the house was dark and still,  

58
00:06:00,240 --> 00:06:08,000
the door to a bedroom cupboard opened and 
Khamel came quietly out. He was dressed  

59
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:13,040
in running clothes. He had shaved off 
his beard and coloured his hair blond.

60
00:06:14,800 --> 00:06:17,360
Silently, he went down the stairs.  

61
00:06:18,560 --> 00:06:24,160
He knew there were two FBI men in a car that was 
parked on the road outside the front of the house;  

62
00:06:25,440 --> 00:06:30,160
he knew there was another guard, Ferguson, 
walking around the house outside.

63
00:06:31,520 --> 00:06:35,760
Rosenberg and his male nurse were 
asleep in the downstairs bedroom.  

64
00:06:37,120 --> 00:06:41,360
Outside the door, Khamel fitted 
a silencer on to his gun.  

65
00:06:42,640 --> 00:06:48,400
He stepped inside, put the gun to the 
head of the nurse and fired three times.  

66
00:06:49,760 --> 00:06:57,760
The hands and legs jumped, but the eyes 
stayed closed, and there was no sound. Khamel  

67
00:06:57,760 --> 00:07:03,360
quickly reached across to the grey old head of 
Judge Rosenberg and shot three bullets into it.

68
00:07:04,960 --> 00:07:11,760
He watched the two bodies for a full minute, 
and then went out to the kitchen. He opened  

69
00:07:11,760 --> 00:07:17,680
the back door, waited until Ferguson appeared 
in the back garden, and then called his name.  

70
00:07:19,120 --> 00:07:23,920
He knew that the nurse often invited Ferguson 
in for a cup of coffee and something to eat.

71
00:07:25,440 --> 00:07:28,080
Ferguson obediently came into the kitchen.  

72
00:07:29,280 --> 00:07:34,720
Khamel fired three bullets into the back of 
his head and he fell loudly on to the table.

73
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:39,600
Khamel left the gun there and 
went out of the back door.  

74
00:07:40,960 --> 00:07:44,880
As soon as he reached the road at the 
back of the house, he began running.

75
00:07:45,920 --> 00:07:49,520
He was just another American, 
out for his nightly run.

76
00:07:50,760 --> 00:07:51,760
***

77
00:07:51,760 --> 00:07:58,320
In the dark of the Montrose Theatre, Glenn 
Jensen sat by himself and watched the men on  

78
00:07:58,320 --> 00:08:05,120
the big screen in the front of the theatre. He 
was dressed in ordinary clothes - clothes that  

79
00:08:05,120 --> 00:08:13,840
no one would remember - and wore dark glasses too. 
Nobody would know that he had been here. He came  

80
00:08:13,840 --> 00:08:21,120
to this homosexual film theatre once or twice a 
week, and not even his FBI guards knew about it.

81
00:08:22,400 --> 00:08:27,520
It was easy to get out of the house. There 
were several apartments in the building,  

82
00:08:27,520 --> 00:08:31,360
and the two FBI men could watch 
only one entrance at a time.  

83
00:08:32,720 --> 00:08:37,040
All he had to do was change his clothes 
and drive away in a friend's car.  

84
00:08:38,640 --> 00:08:44,240
He liked the Montrose because the films went 
on all night and there was never a crowd.  

85
00:08:45,520 --> 00:08:50,560
Tonight there were only two old men, sitting 
together in the middle of the theatre  

86
00:08:50,560 --> 00:08:57,920
and holding hands. Jensen watched their backs and 
wondered if he would be like them in twenty years.  

87
00:08:59,200 --> 00:09:03,040
At forty-four, he was the youngest 
of the Supreme Court judges.

88
00:09:04,640 --> 00:09:10,480
He was not a favourite of either the Republicans 
or the Democrats, but had been a safe appointment  

89
00:09:10,480 --> 00:09:17,360
for the Republican President four years ago. He 
was not particularly liberal, except in cases  

90
00:09:17,360 --> 00:09:24,320
involving homosexuals and those where industry 
threatened the environment. He usually tried to  

91
00:09:24,320 --> 00:09:30,160
judge his cases according to their rights and 
wrongs, rather than any political opinions.

92
00:09:32,720 --> 00:09:37,600
A fourth person entered the theatre where 
Jensen and the two old men were now enjoying  

93
00:09:37,600 --> 00:09:45,120
a film in which several young men were in bed 
together. He wore tight jeans, a black shirt,  

94
00:09:45,120 --> 00:09:50,960
an earring, dark glasses and a 
moustache. Khamel the homosexual.  

95
00:09:52,480 --> 00:09:57,760
He smiled when he saw Jensen there. The 
information they had given him was good.

96
00:09:59,280 --> 00:10:06,160
At 12:20 the old men left the theatre, 
arm in arm. Jensen did not look at them;  

97
00:10:06,720 --> 00:10:14,000
he was too busy watching the film. Khamel 
moved like a cat to a seat behind Jensen.  

98
00:10:15,200 --> 00:10:22,400
He pulled some rope from round his waist and 
wrapped the ends round his hands. He suddenly  

99
00:10:22,400 --> 00:10:27,280
put the rope around the front of Jensen's 
neck and pulled backwards and downwards.  

100
00:10:28,800 --> 00:10:33,920
Jensen's neck broke over the back 
of his seat. Just to make sure,  

101
00:10:34,480 --> 00:10:40,480
Khamel twisted the rope until it bit deeply into 
Jensen's neck and held it there for two minutes.

102
00:10:43,200 --> 00:10:48,080
An hour later he was waiting at Dulles 
airport for his flight to Paris.
 
 
 
 
 

103
00:10:52,320 --> 00:10:53,120
CHAPTER TWO

104
00:10:54,080 --> 00:10:55,200
Political Planning
 

105
00:10:57,120 --> 00:11:00,640
The phone woke the President 
at 4:30 in the morning.  

106
00:11:02,080 --> 00:11:05,600
He listened to the voice for a 
minute and then jumped out of bed.  

107
00:11:06,640 --> 00:11:13,840
Eight minutes later he was in the office. Fletcher 
Coal, his chief of staff, was waiting for him.

108
00:11:15,760 --> 00:11:18,800
'What the hell happened?' the President asked.

109
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:26,400
Coal walked up and down in front of the 
President's desk. 'We don't know much,' he said.  

110
00:11:26,960 --> 00:11:34,640
'They're both dead. Two FBI men found Rosenberg 
at one a.m. His nurse and guard were also dead.

111
00:11:35,440 --> 00:11:41,520
Three bullets each - very clean, very 
professional. While the FBI were at  

112
00:11:41,520 --> 00:11:47,200
Rosenberg's house, they heard that the police 
had found Jensen's body in a homosexual club.  

113
00:11:48,160 --> 00:11:53,040
Voyles called me, and I called 
you. He'll be here in a minute.'

114
00:11:54,560 --> 00:11:57,600
'Rosenberg is dead,' the President said.

115
00:11:58,800 --> 00:12:07,680
'Yes. At last.' Rosenberg and the Republican 
Government had not been friends. 'I suggest  

116
00:12:07,680 --> 00:12:12,800
you go on TV in two or three hours' 
time and tell the country about it all.  

117
00:12:13,920 --> 00:12:20,000
Mabry is already working on your speech. 
We don't want to leave it until later,  

118
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:24,800
because we want to be the first to tell 
them. The press already have the news.'

119
00:12:26,240 --> 00:12:28,560
'I didn't know he was a homosexual.'

120
00:12:30,080 --> 00:12:36,960
'There's no doubt about it now. This is 
the perfect crisis. We didn't cause it;  

121
00:12:36,960 --> 00:12:43,920
we didn't do anything wrong. The country will be 
shocked and they'll turn to you. You're going to  

122
00:12:43,920 --> 00:12:51,840
be more popular than ever, and next year you'll be 
elected again for another four years. It's great.'

123
00:12:52,400 --> 00:12:56,000
'And I can get two new men 
into the Supreme Court.'

124
00:12:57,040 --> 00:13:01,040
'Exactly. That's the best 
bit. They'll be your men,  

125
00:13:01,040 --> 00:13:05,840
and they'll be there for ever. You'll 
have a first list of names by tomorrow.'

126
00:13:07,440 --> 00:13:09,120
'Are there any suspects?'

127
00:13:09,920 --> 00:13:10,480
'Not yet.'

128
00:13:11,600 --> 00:13:18,720
The President smiled. 'Voyles's FBI men were 
supposed to protect the judges, weren't they?  

129
00:13:19,440 --> 00:13:26,960
Good. I want you to leak that information to 
the press. Maybe we can get rid of Voyles too.'

130
00:13:28,720 --> 00:13:33,840
When Voyles arrived a moment later, the 
President and Coal tried to look worried.  

131
00:13:35,360 --> 00:13:38,640
Voyles told them that there were no suspects yet,  

132
00:13:38,640 --> 00:13:41,840
and the President asked for a 
list by five o'clock that evening.  

133
00:13:42,880 --> 00:13:49,520
They agreed that the killings must be connected. 
Voyles denied that his men had been careless.

134
00:13:51,360 --> 00:13:55,280
'Rosenberg and Jensen are dead because they 
refused to let us guard them properly,'  

135
00:13:55,920 --> 00:13:59,840
he said. 'We're guarding the other 
seven, and they're still alive.'

136
00:14:01,440 --> 00:14:08,400
'At the moment,' the President said, 
and looked at Coal. They almost smiled.  

137
00:14:09,440 --> 00:14:13,680
They could easily make Voyles look stupid 
and inefficient over this business.  

138
00:14:14,800 --> 00:14:18,720
Voyles knew it too. He was 
going to have to be careful.  

139
00:14:20,080 --> 00:14:26,720
The President - or rather Coal, who told the 
President what to think - wanted his head, and  

140
00:14:26,720 --> 00:14:33,760
the press would eat him alive. Back in his office, 
he ordered a full enquiry into the murders.

141
00:14:35,320 --> 00:14:36,320
***

142
00:14:36,320 --> 00:14:44,000
Darby Shaw woke up a little before dawn. After 
fifteen months of law school at Tulane University  

143
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:51,600
in New Orleans, her mind refused to rest for more 
than six hours. The work had not been so hard at  

144
00:14:51,600 --> 00:14:57,840
her first university, in Phoenix, Arizona, where 
she had specialized in environmental science.  

145
00:14:58,640 --> 00:15:03,280
Then she decided to become a lawyer and 
to defend the environment in the courts.  

146
00:15:04,320 --> 00:15:08,320
The price was hard work and more hard work.

147
00:15:09,760 --> 00:15:15,840
There were some rewards, however. She turned 
over in the bed to look at the man sleeping  

148
00:15:15,840 --> 00:15:22,960
next to her. Thomas Callahan was one of the 
most popular teachers in the university. He was  

149
00:15:22,960 --> 00:15:30,960
forty-five years old, but seemed a lot younger. 
He drank a lot, wore jeans, drove a Porsche, lived  

150
00:15:30,960 --> 00:15:37,840
in the French Quarter and managed to make even 
constitutional law interesting. He was also good  

151
00:15:37,840 --> 00:15:44,640
in bed. And for the first time in his life he had 
stayed with one woman for more than a few weeks.  

152
00:15:46,480 --> 00:15:52,560
Darby and he had been together now for 
several months. She smiled and wondered  

153
00:15:52,560 --> 00:15:58,000
what her fellow students would think. Only 
her very best friends knew the secret.

154
00:15:59,920 --> 00:16:06,640
She turned the TV on and suddenly there was the 
President. She listened for a minute and then  

155
00:16:06,640 --> 00:16:15,920
shook Thomas awake. 'Thomas! Wake up! Listen 
to this!' She turned the sound up louder.

156
00:16:17,040 --> 00:16:23,120
Callahan sat up and stared at the screen, still 
half asleep. He understood what the President  

157
00:16:23,120 --> 00:16:33,040
was saying, though. 'Rosenberg? Murdered?' he 
said. Darby knew that Rosenberg was his hero.

158
00:16:34,160 --> 00:16:36,160
'Jensen too,' she said.

159
00:16:37,360 --> 00:16:40,560
The President finished his speech 
and Darby switched the TV off.

160
00:16:42,640 --> 00:16:46,320
'No suspects, according to 
the President,' Callahan said.

161
00:16:47,200 --> 00:16:51,840
'I can think of at least twenty groups 
who wanted Rosenberg dead,' Darby said,  

162
00:16:52,480 --> 00:16:54,240
'starting with the Ku-Klux-Klan.'

163
00:16:55,520 --> 00:17:01,360
'Yeah, but why those two judges? OK, 
lots of people wanted Rosenberg dead,  

164
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:08,240
but why Jensen? Why not McDowell or Yount? 
They're both more liberal than Jensen.'

165
00:17:09,600 --> 00:17:12,800
'Maybe they both just got killed 
on the same night by chance,'

166
00:17:13,840 --> 00:17:15,920
Darby suggested, without believing it.

167
00:17:16,720 --> 00:17:23,440
'No, I don't think so,' said Callahan. 'These 
are the first Supreme Court judges ever to be  

168
00:17:23,440 --> 00:17:28,800
murdered - and then two in one night? There 
must be some connection between the murders.  

169
00:17:30,400 --> 00:17:35,040
But you know the worst thing? That 
fool President will be able to fill  

170
00:17:35,040 --> 00:17:39,680
their places. That means that eight 
out of the nine will be Republicans.  

171
00:17:40,480 --> 00:17:45,840
We won't be able to recognize the 
Constitution in ten years. This is awful.'

172
00:17:46,960 --> 00:17:48,960
'Perhaps that's why they were killed, Thomas.  

173
00:17:49,840 --> 00:17:55,600
Someone or some group wants a different 
Supreme Court, filled with Republicans.'

174
00:17:56,720 --> 00:18:00,480
'But why Jensen? He was 
appointed by a Republican.'

175
00:18:01,680 --> 00:18:04,880
'I don't know, but there must be some connection.  

176
00:18:06,080 --> 00:18:10,080
Maybe there's a clue in the cases the 
Supreme Court was due to hear this year.  

177
00:18:10,880 --> 00:18:15,600
The library will have that information. I think 
I'll spend some time on this today.'
 
 
 
 
 

178
00:18:19,680 --> 00:18:20,400
CHAPTER THREE

179
00:18:21,280 --> 00:18:22,080
No Clues
 

180
00:18:24,240 --> 00:18:31,760
Denton Voyles put Eric East in charge of the 
case. On Thursday, East reported back to Voyles  

181
00:18:31,760 --> 00:18:39,040
with a list of their top suspects. There were 
a number of political groups - especially the  

182
00:18:39,040 --> 00:18:46,960
Underground Army, the Ku-Klux-Klan and the White 
Defenders - but also some individuals who were  

183
00:18:46,960 --> 00:18:51,680
rich enough to afford the kind of professional 
killer who had obviously done this job.  

184
00:18:53,120 --> 00:18:58,080
There was Nelson Muncie, who had lost 
his daughter in a sex killing in Florida;  

185
00:18:59,200 --> 00:19:03,760
the police had caught the man, who 
was black, but thanks to Rosenberg  

186
00:19:03,760 --> 00:19:11,200
the man had walked free. There was Clinton Lane, 
whose son was a homosexual who had died of Aids.  

187
00:19:12,560 --> 00:19:18,320
The problem with all these suspects, however, was 
that the killings were so professional and clean  

188
00:19:18,880 --> 00:19:22,000
that there were no clues except 
for the gun and the rope.  

189
00:19:23,120 --> 00:19:30,320
There were not even any clues about how the killer 
had entered Rosenberg's house. Still, Voyles and  

190
00:19:30,320 --> 00:19:37,840
he agreed to have between five and twenty men 
investigate each suspect or group of suspects.

191
00:19:38,880 --> 00:19:42,640
In the law library and on the 
computers of Tulane University,  

192
00:19:43,360 --> 00:19:46,800
Darby Shaw was gathering pages 
and pages of information.

193
00:19:48,240 --> 00:19:54,640
What was the connection between Rosenberg and 
Jensen? She could see reasons for killing one  

194
00:19:54,640 --> 00:20:00,560
or the other, but not both together. 
But there had to be a single reason.

195
00:20:02,840 --> 00:20:03,840
***

196
00:20:03,840 --> 00:20:10,240
Thomas Callahan slept late and alone. Darby 
had been too busy to see him since Wednesday.  

