Now it was Friday morning. 
He made some coffee and,  

198
00:20:15,680 --> 00:20:19,840
as he drank it, watched the busy 
French Quarter through his window.

199
00:20:20,560 --> 00:20:28,480
What was it he had to do? Oh, yes, phone 
Gavin. On Monday he was going to Washington  

200
00:20:28,480 --> 00:20:35,680
for a conference about constitutional law. He 
and his old friend Gavin Verheek were going to  

201
00:20:35,680 --> 00:20:41,840
meet and get drunk together on Monday evening. 
Gavin had been a friend ever since law school.  

202
00:20:43,040 --> 00:20:48,000
He and Callahan were the only two in their year 
who refused to go into private practice and  

203
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:55,440
get rich. While Callahan had become a teacher, 
Verheek had joined the FBI as a legal adviser.

204
00:20:57,120 --> 00:21:02,160
When Verheek came on the phone, 
he said, 'Thomas, how are you?'

205
00:21:03,760 --> 00:21:07,440
'It's ten-thirty. I'm not dressed. 
I'm sitting here in the French  

206
00:21:07,440 --> 00:21:11,760
Quarter drinking coffee and watching 
the world outside. What are you doing?'

207
00:21:12,800 --> 00:21:15,120
'Well, here it's eleven-thirty,  

208
00:21:15,840 --> 00:21:19,840
and I haven't left the office since they 
found the bodies on Wednesday morning.'

209
00:21:21,760 --> 00:21:27,040
'It makes me sick, Gavin. The President 
will get two Nazis on to the Supreme Court.  

210
00:21:27,920 --> 00:21:33,600
I suppose you've already seen the list. I bet 
your office is already checking that they've  

211
00:21:33,600 --> 00:21:42,320
lived good, clean lives. Go on, Gavin, tell me 
who's on the list. I won't tell anyone else.'

212
00:21:43,600 --> 00:21:48,400
'No chance. I'll only tell you 
this: your name's not on the list'

213
00:21:49,840 --> 00:21:51,120
'I'm so disappointed.'

214
00:21:51,760 --> 00:21:52,640
'How's the girl?'

215
00:21:53,680 --> 00:21:54,240
'Which one?'

216
00:21:55,120 --> 00:21:57,840
'Come on, Thomas. The girl?'

217
00:21:58,720 --> 00:22:02,880
'She's beautiful and brilliant and gentle. Oh,  

218
00:22:03,520 --> 00:22:08,560
and rich. She has red hair and the 
longest legs you've ever seen.'

219
00:22:09,760 --> 00:22:11,840
'Wow! What's her name?'

220
00:22:13,040 --> 00:22:19,680
'Darby Shaw. But I haven't seen her for a couple 
of days. She's trying to solve the murders all  

221
00:22:19,680 --> 00:22:26,720
by herself. Why don't you tell me who did it, and 
then I can tell her and she'll come back to me?'

222
00:22:27,920 --> 00:22:32,640
'Don't you read the papers? 
We have no suspects. Not one.'

223
00:22:33,920 --> 00:22:37,680
'At least I tried. Are we 
going to meet on Monday?'

224
00:22:38,720 --> 00:22:44,320
'I hope so. Voyles wants us to work day and 
night until the computers tell us who did it.'

225
00:22:45,600 --> 00:22:49,840
'I'll expect a full report on 
Monday, Gavin - not just the gossip.'

226
00:22:50,800 --> 00:22:54,960
'Why don't you bring Darby? 
How old is she? Nineteen?'

227
00:22:56,240 --> 00:22:58,640
'Twenty-four, and she's not invited.  

228
00:22:59,520 --> 00:23:04,080
I'll see you on Monday at seven 
p.m., in the usual restaurant. OK?'

229
00:23:05,120 --> 00:23:08,280
'OK. See you.'

230
00:23:08,280 --> 00:23:09,280
***

231
00:23:09,280 --> 00:23:15,680
Darby's enquiries had brought her to the court 
in Lafayette. Of all the Supreme Court cases due  

232
00:23:15,680 --> 00:23:20,080
to be heard in the next few months, there 
was one that could explain the killings.  

233
00:23:21,200 --> 00:23:28,160
She needed to see the court's files on the case. 
When the clerk brought them to her table, however,  

234
00:23:28,800 --> 00:23:37,120
her heart sank. There were lots of files, each 
inches thick. The case was seven years old.  

235
00:23:38,160 --> 00:23:43,920
Only one person was involved, but he had hidden 
behind thirty-eight different businesses,  

236
00:23:43,920 --> 00:23:50,240
which had used no fewer than fifteen 
law firms over the last seven years.

237
00:23:50,240 --> 00:23:53,840
She pulled her chair in to the 
table and began to work.
 
 
 
 
 

238
00:23:58,080 --> 00:23:58,880
CHAPTER FOUR

239
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:04,240
Ideas and Information
 

240
00:24:04,240 --> 00:24:10,960
The meeting East and Voyles had with Coal and 
the President did not go well. Not only could  

241
00:24:10,960 --> 00:24:16,160
they not report any progress, but they had to 
admit that investigations like this could take  

242
00:24:16,160 --> 00:24:22,720
many months. Then Coal handed Voyles a list of 
eight possible members of the Supreme Court,  

243
00:24:23,600 --> 00:24:31,200
two of whom would fill the places left empty by 
Rosenberg and Jensen. 'We want a report on these  

244
00:24:31,200 --> 00:24:37,600
people in ten days, Voyles,' he said, 'and make 
sure the press doesn't get to hear about them.'

245
00:24:39,440 --> 00:24:46,480
'You know we can't promise that,' Voyles 
said. 'We can't guarantee no leaks. As soon  

246
00:24:46,480 --> 00:24:50,720
as we start to dig around these people, 
someone will realize what's going on.'

247
00:24:51,920 --> 00:24:54,480
'The FBI can't guarantee secrecy?'  

248
00:24:55,280 --> 00:24:59,840
Coal said. 'You'd better keep 
this out of the papers, Voyles.'

249
00:25:00,560 --> 00:25:05,520
Voyles jumped out of his chair. 
'Listen, Coal,' he shouted.  

250
00:25:06,960 --> 00:25:11,600
'Why don't you investigate these people 
yourself? Don't start telling me what to do.'

251
00:25:13,120 --> 00:25:18,880
The President tried to make peace. 'All 
we're saying is do your best, Voyles,'  

252
00:25:19,520 --> 00:25:24,000
he said. 'These people are young 
and they're good Republicans.  

253
00:25:24,880 --> 00:25:30,720
They'll be giving the Constitution shape long 
after I'm dead. So it's important to me that  

254
00:25:30,720 --> 00:25:36,480
the two who become members of the Supreme Court 
are clean, so that they can stay there for ever.  

255
00:25:37,440 --> 00:25:42,960
So no drugs, no unusual sexual 
habits - nothing like that. OK?'

256
00:25:44,400 --> 00:25:48,560
'Yes, Mr President. But we 
cannot guarantee total secrecy.'

257
00:25:49,760 --> 00:25:52,800
'I understand. Just try your best.'

258
00:25:54,320 --> 00:25:55,840
'Yes, sir.'

259
00:25:56,680 --> 00:25:57,680
***

260
00:25:57,680 --> 00:26:00,960
Callahan went round to 
Darby's apartment with a pizza  

261
00:26:00,960 --> 00:26:07,040
and a bottle of wine. He hadn't seen her 
for four days. He rang on her doorbell.

262
00:26:08,480 --> 00:26:10,800
'Who is it?' she called through the door.

263
00:26:12,240 --> 00:26:15,520
'Thomas Callahan,' he said. 'Do you remember me?'

264
00:26:16,960 --> 00:26:25,200
The door opened and Callahan stepped in. 'Are we 
still friends?' he asked, and gave her a kiss.

265
00:26:26,160 --> 00:26:28,800
'Of course. I've just been busy.'

266
00:26:29,840 --> 00:26:31,760
'So what did the great detective find?'

267
00:26:33,120 --> 00:26:36,320
She was opening the bottle of wine 
and didn't answer straight away.  

268
00:26:37,360 --> 00:26:41,600
She poured wine into two glasses and 
they went and sat together on the sofa.  

269
00:26:42,720 --> 00:26:47,760
She put her legs up on to him, and he 
stroked them. He repeated the question.

270
00:26:49,360 --> 00:26:53,840
'Nothing, really. I was following 
a path, and it took me somewhere.  

271
00:26:54,640 --> 00:26:58,480
I even typed it up as a brief, but 
I don't think it's worth anything.'

272
00:26:59,600 --> 00:27:05,280
'What? You've been running around playing 
detective for four days, and refusing to see me,  

273
00:27:05,280 --> 00:27:07,760
and now you're just going to throw it away?'

274
00:27:08,880 --> 00:27:12,480
'It's over there on the table, 
if you want to see it,' she said.

275
00:27:13,760 --> 00:27:19,840
'I don't want to see it now,' he said. 
'We have more important things to do.  

276
00:27:21,280 --> 00:27:25,200
I'm going to be away in Washington 
for a few days, remember?  

277
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:34,080
I'll read your brief and then we'll talk 
about it. But not till we've been to bed, OK?'

278
00:27:34,080 --> 00:27:37,680
She pulled him towards her 
and they kissed long and hard.

279
00:27:38,680 --> 00:27:39,680
***

280
00:27:39,680 --> 00:27:46,560
There was a cleaner in the White House whom 
everyone called Sarge. He was old, very black,  

281
00:27:46,560 --> 00:27:53,440
and had white hair. He wore dark glasses all the 
time, and everyone thought that he was half blind.

282
00:27:54,560 --> 00:28:02,080
In fact, Sarge could see very 
well. He could see round corners.  

283
00:28:02,080 --> 00:28:08,240
He had been working in the White House for thirty 
years now, cleaning and listening, cleaning  

284
00:28:08,880 --> 00:28:17,120
and seeing. He knew which doors stayed open and 
which walls were thin. No one ever noticed him.

285
00:28:18,720 --> 00:28:27,040
His son Cleve was a policeman. This is how it 
worked: Cleve would contact Gray Grantham of  

286
00:28:27,040 --> 00:28:34,560
the Washington Post and arrange a meeting. 
Sarge and Grantham would meet. No one knew  

287
00:28:34,560 --> 00:28:40,800
how Grantham got his political information, 
but it was always good and always correct.  

288
00:28:42,240 --> 00:28:49,040
Sarge never talked to anyone except Grantham, and 
he didn't tell even him everything he found out.

289
00:28:50,560 --> 00:28:58,320
This time they met at Glenda's, a little cafe 
on Fourteenth Street. Sarge was able to tell  

290
00:28:58,320 --> 00:29:02,640
Grantham two of the people on the list 
of possible Supreme Court judges.
 
 
 
 
 

291
00:29:06,800 --> 00:29:07,680
CHAPTER FIVE

292
00:29:08,560 --> 00:29:11,880
An Implausible Theory
 

293
00:29:11,880 --> 00:29:15,920
Verheek had drunk too much the 
night before with Callahan,  

294
00:29:15,920 --> 00:29:22,480
as he had known he would. What had he 
said? Had he given away any secrets?  

295
00:29:24,160 --> 00:29:28,880
He remembered explaining that the connection 
between Rosenberg and Jensen was not political.  

296
00:29:29,920 --> 00:29:35,520
The connection was so obvious that for 
several days no one in the FBI had seen it.

297
00:29:36,560 --> 00:29:39,600
They were killed because the 
killer could get to them.  

298
00:29:39,600 --> 00:29:44,240
It was as simple as that. They 
weren't guarded as well as the others.  

299
00:29:45,840 --> 00:29:51,280
Of course this still didn't answer the question 
why someone wanted two Supreme Court judges dead.

300
00:29:53,120 --> 00:29:57,600
He remembered that they spent most of the evening 
talking about their student days together in  

301
00:29:57,600 --> 00:30:05,600
Washington, and about women. Callahan had given 
him a copy of the brief his girl-friend - what  

302
00:30:05,600 --> 00:30:13,040
was her name? Darby - had written about the 
death of the two judges. Callahan had said it  

303
00:30:13,040 --> 00:30:19,280
was an interesting theory. She didn't believe 
it, nor did he, but it was worth reading.

304
00:30:21,520 --> 00:30:25,280
Verheek pulled the brief out of his 
briefcase now and started to read it.  

305
00:30:26,400 --> 00:30:32,560
It was better written than most briefs, and 
he enjoyed it. The theory was implausible,  

306
00:30:32,560 --> 00:30:39,360
but no one else had thought of it. It was worth 
considering. He would show it to Eric East.

307
00:30:41,320 --> 00:30:42,320
***

308
00:30:42,320 --> 00:30:46,880
The phone went four times, 
the answering machine came on,  

309
00:30:46,880 --> 00:30:53,520
but the caller left no message. The phone 
went again, and the same thing happened again.  

310
00:30:55,120 --> 00:31:03,840
The third time Grantham climbed out of bed and 
answered the phone. It was still dark. 'Yes?'

311
00:31:05,440 --> 00:31:09,120
'Is that Gray Grantham, of the Washington Post?'

312
00:31:10,640 --> 00:31:12,640
'It is. Who's calling?'

313
00:31:14,320 --> 00:31:15,600
'I can't give you my name.'

314
00:31:16,880 --> 00:31:19,360
'OK. Why are you calling?'

315
00:31:20,720 --> 00:31:26,880
'I saw your story yesterday about the White House 
and the possible next two Supreme Court judges.'

316
00:31:28,320 --> 00:31:32,720
'Good. But why are you calling 
me so early in the morning?'

317
00:31:34,240 --> 00:31:42,320
'I'm sorry. I'm in a pay phone. I'm on my way 
to work. I can't call from home or the office.'

318
00:31:43,440 --> 00:31:45,920
'What kind of office?'

319
00:31:45,920 --> 00:31:46,800
'I'm a lawyer.'

320
00:31:48,320 --> 00:31:54,800
Great. Washington was home to half a 
million lawyers. 'Private or government?'

321
00:31:56,080 --> 00:31:57,200
'I'd rather not say.'

322
00:31:58,720 --> 00:32:01,360
'OK. Anyway, why did you call?'

323
00:32:02,880 --> 00:32:08,240
A hesitation. 'I may know something 
about Rosenberg and Jensen.'

324
00:32:09,360 --> 00:32:14,320
Grantham sat up straight. 'What, exactly?'

325
00:32:14,320 --> 00:32:15,440
'Are you recording this?'

326
00:32:16,640 --> 00:32:18,000
'No. Should I?'

327
00:32:19,440 --> 00:32:25,520
'I don't know, Mr Grantham. I'd prefer 
it if you didn't record this. OK?'

328
00:32:26,960 --> 00:32:29,040
'Whatever you want. I'm listening.'

329
00:32:30,480 --> 00:32:31,680
'Can you trace this call?'

330
00:32:33,120 --> 00:32:37,360
'I could. But you're at a pay phone 
- what difference would it make?'

331
00:32:38,560 --> 00:32:45,200
'You're right. I'm just frightened. You 
see, I think I know who killed them.'

332
00:32:46,320 --> 00:32:50,320
Now Grantham was standing. 
'That's valuable information.'

333
00:32:51,520 --> 00:32:56,080
'It could get me killed. Do you 
think they're following me?'

334
00:32:56,080 --> 00:32:59,360
'Who? Don't worry. Tell me your name.'

335
00:33:00,800 --> 00:33:02,240
'You can call me Garcia.'

336
00:33:03,440 --> 00:33:04,960
'That's not your real name, is it?

337
00:33:06,480 --> 00:33:10,000
'Of course not, but it's the best I can do.'

338
00:33:10,000 --> 00:33:12,320
'OK, Garcia, talk to me.'

339
00:33:14,080 --> 00:33:19,040
'I'm not certain, you understand. But 
I think I accidentally saw something  

340
00:33:19,040 --> 00:33:21,200
at the office that I was not supposed to see.'

341
00:33:22,240 --> 00:33:23,840
'Do you have a copy of it?'

342
00:33:24,720 --> 00:33:25,040
'Maybe.'

343
00:33:26,080 --> 00:33:27,680
'Do you want to talk or not?'

344
00:33:29,120 --> 00:33:33,120
'I don't know. What will you 
do if I tell you something?'

345
00:33:34,160 --> 00:33:39,520
'First try to find out whether it's true. We won't 
print the names of the killers of two Supreme  

346
00:33:39,520 --> 00:33:47,520
Court judges in a hurry, believe me.' There was a 
very long silence. 'Garcia, are you still there?'

347
00:33:48,960 --> 00:33:53,840
'Yes. I need to think about 
this. I might call you later.'

348
00:33:54,880 --> 00:33:56,880
'OK, if that's what you want.'

349
00:33:58,160 --> 00:33:59,280
'Sorry I woke you up.'

350
00:34:00,640 --> 00:34:07,120
The phone went dead. Grantham pushed seven 
numbers on his phone, waited, and then pushed  

351
00:34:07,120 --> 00:34:14,800
six more. Another wait, and then four more. 
The small screen on his phone showed him a row  

352
00:34:14,800 --> 00:34:21,680
of numbers. He wrote them down on a piece of 
paper. The pay phone was on Fifteenth Street.

353
00:34:24,920 --> 00:34:25,920
***

354
00:34:25,920 --> 00:34:32,480
East and K. O. Lewis, Voyles's second-in-command, 
met with Coal alone, because the President  

355
00:34:32,480 --> 00:34:39,680
was out of Washington. They had two bits of 
information for him. First, they told him that  

356
00:34:39,680 --> 00:34:45,680
cameras at the airport in Paris had recorded 
the arrival from Dulles of the killer Khamel.

357
00:34:47,440 --> 00:34:49,040
Coal thought about this for a minute.  

358
00:34:50,400 --> 00:34:54,400
'What if Khamel was involved in 
the killings? What does it mean?'

359
00:34:56,080 --> 00:34:58,000
'It means we'll never find him,'  

360
00:34:58,880 --> 00:35:05,200
Lewis replied. 'Nine countries around the world 
have failed to find him for the last twenty years.  

361
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:11,120
It means that he was paid a lot of money by 
someone or some people here to do the killings.'

362
00:35:12,960 --> 00:35:19,200
'So we know or we think that Khamel did the 
killings, but it doesn't really help us, does it?'

363
00:35:20,480 --> 00:35:22,000
No, you're right.'

364
00:35:23,360 --> 00:35:26,400
'OK. What else have you got for me?'

365
00:35:27,680 --> 00:35:33,520
Lewis looked at East. 'There's no 
real progress to report, except.

366
00:35:34,480 --> 00:35:35,360
'Except what?'

367
00:35:36,480 --> 00:35:41,600
'Well, there's this theory which has 
appeared in the last twenty- four hours.  

368
00:35:42,480 --> 00:35:48,400
A law student in New Orleans wrote it up 
as a brief. We call it the Pelican Brief.  

369
00:35:49,440 --> 00:35:54,880
Here's a copy of it. Voyles liked it, but 
he was afraid it could hurt the President.'

370
00:35:56,000 --> 00:35:56,320
'How?'

371
00:35:57,600 --> 00:35:59,600
'Read it. You'll see.'

372
00:36:01,320 --> 00:36:02,320
***

373
00:36:02,320 --> 00:36:05,520
This time Garcia called 
Grantham during office hours.  

374
00:36:06,320 --> 00:36:11,840
He didn't tell him anything new. He 
was still frightened and uncertain.

375
00:36:12,720 --> 00:36:15,920
They agreed that he would call 
again at lunch-time the next day.  

376
00:36:17,040 --> 00:36:20,720
The call came from a pay 
phone on Pennsylvania Avenue.

377
00:36:21,800 --> 00:36:22,800
***

378
00:36:22,800 --> 00:36:29,920
Later, when the President returned, Coal told 
him about the brief. 'The theory is implausible,'  

379
00:36:30,480 --> 00:36:37,040
he said. 'But Voyles likes it. He probably doesn't 
believe the theory any more than anyone else,  

380
00:36:37,680 --> 00:36:40,800
but we've made him look bad 
over these killings so far  

381
00:36:41,360 --> 00:36:48,560
and he wants revenge. He's going to investigate 
this new suspect. If the press get to hear about  

382
00:36:48,560 --> 00:36:54,560
the investigation, that could be bad for 
you. We'd better do something about it.'

383
00:36:56,000 --> 00:36:58,080
'Is the suspect someone we know?'

384
00:36:59,360 --> 00:37:02,800
'Yes.' Coal explained what was in the brief.

385
00:37:04,400 --> 00:37:06,480
'Did we get a lot of money from him?'

386
00:37:07,840 --> 00:37:14,640
'Millions, one way or another,' said Coal. 
But the President preferred not to know the  

387
00:37:14,640 --> 00:37:21,840
various ways in which money came in, especially 
when they weren't always perfectly legal.
 
 
 
 
 

388
00:37:25,520 --> 00:37:26,320
CHAPTER SIX

389
00:37:27,440 --> 00:37:27,920
Hunted!
 

390
00:37:30,080 --> 00:37:35,840
Thomas was drinking too much over dinner. 
She didn't like it, and she told him so.  

391
00:37:36,880 --> 00:37:42,800
He wanted to prove that she was wrong, so 
he drank even more. They had an argument.

392
00:37:44,240 --> 00:37:49,840
After dinner, outside the restaurant, he pulled 
the keys to his Porsche out of his pocket.

393
00:37:50,640 --> 00:37:55,040
'Thomas, no! You're too drunk 
to drive. Give me the keys.'

394
00:37:56,160 --> 00:38:01,520
He held on to the keys and set off in the 
direction of the car park. He couldn't walk  

395
00:38:01,520 --> 00:38:07,360
straight and his foot kept slipping off the 
pavement into the road. She followed him,  

396
00:38:07,360 --> 00:38:14,000
but stayed some way behind; she was too angry, and 
just wanted to get back to her apartment alone.  

397
00:38:15,520 --> 00:38:20,480
He shouted something over his shoulder about 
how he could drive better when he was drunk.

398
00:38:22,960 --> 00:38:26,320
She stood with her arms crossed 
on the other side of the car park  

399
00:38:26,320 --> 00:38:34,160
and watched him put the key into the lock. It 
took him three or four attempts. Then he was  

400
00:38:34,160 --> 00:38:40,480
inside and she lost sight of him between two other 
cars. She heard him start the engine, though.

401
00:38:42,160 --> 00:38:44,480
The explosion knocked her to the ground.  

402
00:38:45,600 --> 00:38:51,840
She lay there for a moment, and then jumped 
to her feet. The Porsche was a ball of fire.

403
00:38:53,440 --> 00:38:59,920
Darby ran towards it, screaming his name. Bits 
of the car were still falling all around her,  

404
00:38:59,920 --> 00:39:05,520
and the heat stopped her thirty feet away. 
She screamed with her hands over her mouth.

405
00:39:07,040 --> 00:39:10,560
A second explosion tore through 
the car and pushed her back.  

406
00:39:11,520 --> 00:39:18,000
She fell and her head hit the side of a parked 
car hard. Everything went blank for a minute.

407
00:39:19,120 --> 00:39:22,160
Then there were people 
everywhere, and voices shouting:

408
00:39:22,800 --> 00:39:27,840
'Whose car is it? Call 911! 
Was there anyone in it?'

409
00:39:28,720 --> 00:39:35,440
She was repeating the name Thomas. Someone put 
a cold cloth on her head. She heard the sound  

410
00:39:35,440 --> 00:39:41,840
of the police and firemen coming, and then 
there were red and blue lights everywhere.

411
00:39:42,400 --> 00:39:48,480
A black man was bending over her. 
'Are you all right, miss?' he asked.

412
00:39:49,840 --> 00:39:52,960
'Thomas,' she said. 'Where's Thomas?'

413
00:39:54,320 --> 00:39:59,440
'Miss, who's Thomas?' asked 
the man. 'Was he in that car?'

414
00:40:00,800 --> 00:40:07,200
She nodded and then closed her eyes. She could 
hear men shouting in the distance. They were all  

415
00:40:07,200 --> 00:40:14,160
over by the burning car. She sat up and was 
sick between her legs. Then she felt better.

416
00:40:15,120 --> 00:40:23,840
She got up and walked away. She knew who the 
bomb had been for: her. And she knew why.

417
00:40:25,200 --> 00:40:29,520
She had to hide; they were hunting 
her. Were they behind her even now?  

418
00:40:30,880 --> 00:40:38,160
She wandered deep into the French Quarter, found a 
cheap hotel and paid for a room with her card. As  

419
00:40:38,160 --> 00:40:43,520
soon as she was in the room, she locked the door 
and curled up on the bed with all the lights on.

420
00:40:44,680 --> 00:40:45,680
***

421
00:40:45,680 --> 00:40:48,240
Mrs Verheek answered the bedside phone.  

422
00:40:49,040 --> 00:40:53,440
'It's for you, Gavin,' she called into 
the bathroom, where he was shaving.

423
00:40:54,320 --> 00:40:55,920
He came and took the phone from her.  

424
00:40:56,720 --> 00:41:01,440
'Hello,' he said angrily. Who could 
be calling this early in the morning?

425
00:41:02,800 --> 00:41:05,840
'This is Darby Shaw. Do you know the name?'

426
00:41:06,800 --> 00:41:08,800
'Yes. We share a friend.'

427
00:41:10,080 --> 00:41:12,000
'Did you read the little theory I wrote?'

428
00:41:13,280 --> 00:41:16,000
'Yes, the Pelican Brief, as we call it.'

429
00:41:17,120 --> 00:41:20,240
'And who is "we"?'

430
00:41:20,240 --> 00:41:26,960
Verheek sat up straight. She was not calling for 
a friendly chat. 'Why are you calling, Darby?'

431
00:41:27,920 --> 00:41:31,840
'I need some answers, Mr Verheek. 
I'm frightened to death.'

432
00:41:33,440 --> 00:41:35,440
'It's Gavin, OK?'

433
00:41:36,480 --> 00:41:38,960
'OK, Gavin. Where's the brief?'

434
00:41:39,840 --> 00:41:41,600
'Why? What's wrong?'

435
00:41:42,640 --> 00:41:46,320
'I'll tell you in a minute. Just 
tell me what you did with the brief.'

436
00:41:47,520 --> 00:41:50,960
'Well, I read it, and then I 
passed it on to someone else,  

437
00:41:50,960 --> 00:41:54,160
who passed it on to Denton Voyles, who liked it.'

438
00:41:55,040 --> 00:41:57,360
'Has anyone outside the FBI seen it?'

439
00:41:58,240 --> 00:41:59,760
'I can't answer that.'

440
00:42:00,640 --> 00:42:02,800
'Then I won't tell you what's happened to Thomas.'

441
00:42:03,760 --> 00:42:07,040
'All right. Yes, it's been outside the FBI,  

442
00:42:07,040 --> 00:42:11,520
but I don't know exactly where and I 
don't know how many people have read it.'

443
00:42:12,880 --> 00:42:20,560
'He's dead, Gavin. He was murdered last night. 
Someone put a bomb in the car. I was lucky.'

444
00:42:22,240 --> 00:42:26,640
Gavin was shocked. 'Where are you? Are you safe?'

445
00:42:27,680 --> 00:42:34,480
'New Orleans. Who knows if I'm safe? They must 
be after me too. It was me they really wanted.'

446
00:42:35,680 --> 00:42:38,160
'I'll have some men come and get you, Darby.  

447
00:42:38,160 --> 00:42:42,880
You can't stay on the streets. Then I'll 
catch a plane and I'll be there by midday.'

448
00:42:43,760 --> 00:42:47,520
'I don't think so. Thomas is 
dead because he talked to you.  

449
00:42:48,400 --> 00:42:54,320
Why should I want to talk to you? Give me 
your number at work. I may call you later.'

450
00:42:55,360 --> 00:43:00,880
'OK. But Darby, just tell 
me: did he feel any pain?'

451
00:43:02,320 --> 00:43:10,880
There were tears in her voice. 'No, it was very 
quick.' Then she put the phone down. She could  

452
00:43:10,880 --> 00:43:17,600
let herself cry now, because there wouldn't be 
time later. Crying could get her killed.
 
 
 
 
 

453
00:43:21,760 --> 00:43:22,560
CHAPTER SEVEN

454
00:43:23,520 --> 00:43:26,240
Keep Moving
 

455
00:43:26,240 --> 00:43:29,520
It was nearly time for the 
President's daily meeting with Voyles.  

456
00:43:30,720 --> 00:43:36,800
By now he was tired of the whole business; he 
just wanted to get his men into the Supreme Court.  

457
00:43:38,320 --> 00:43:41,600
Coal was telling him something, 
but he wasn't really listening.  

458
00:43:43,280 --> 00:43:49,040
Voyles and Coal hated each other so much now that 
Coal had to leave the office whenever Voyles came.  

459
00:43:50,000 --> 00:43:51,760
They had nearly fought last time.  

460
00:43:53,440 --> 00:43:58,880
It didn't matter to Coal whether he was 
in or out of the office; there were enough  

461
00:43:58,880 --> 00:44:03,120
hidden microphones and cameras for him to 
listen and watch any conversation there.

462
00:44:05,040 --> 00:44:11,120
The President felt better knowing that Coal was 
at least watching. He greeted Voyles warmly at  

463
00:44:11,120 --> 00:44:17,440
the door and led him over to the sofa for 
a friendly chat. Voyles was not impressed.

464
00:44:19,800 --> 00:44:25,920
'Denton,' the President said, 'I want to 
apologize for Coal's be-haviour last time.'

465
00:44:27,280 --> 00:44:32,320
'He can be stupid, can't he?' Voyles 
said, knowing that Coal was listening.

466
00:44:33,600 --> 00:44:42,240
'Yes. He's very clever, and works amazingly 
hard, but he goes too far sometimes. Anyway,  

467
00:44:42,240 --> 00:44:47,840
that's all behind us now. I want you to 
tell me all about this Pelican Brief.  

468
00:44:48,560 --> 00:44:50,480
How seriously are you taking it?'

469
00:44:52,000 --> 00:44:59,200
Voyles tried not to smile. This was great - he 
had managed to get Coal and the President worried.  

470
00:45:00,800 --> 00:45:07,520
'We are investigating all suspects, Mr President,' 
he replied. 'We have fourteen men on this one.'

471
00:45:08,960 --> 00:45:12,880
'I don't have to tell you, 
Denton,' the President continued,  

472
00:45:13,600 --> 00:45:17,840
'how much damage this theory could 
do if the press heard about it.'

473
00:45:18,720 --> 00:45:20,560
'We won't tell the press, Mr President.'

474
00:45:21,760 --> 00:45:27,120
'I know. All I'm saying is that I 
want you to pull back from this one.  

475
00:45:27,920 --> 00:45:35,440
The theory is crazy anyway, and I could really 
get hurt. Do you understand what I'm saying?'

476
00:45:36,560 --> 00:45:40,240
'Are you asking me not to 
investigate a suspect, Mr President?'

477
00:45:41,760 --> 00:45:46,160
'I'm just saying that you must have 
better things to do with your men.  

478
00:45:47,200 --> 00:45:53,680
The press is watching this investigation closely. 
You know how they are - they don't like me at all.  

479
00:45:54,560 --> 00:45:59,840
So why don't you leave this one 
alone and chase the real suspects?'

480
00:46:00,400 --> 00:46:02,160
'Is that what you're asking me to do?'

481
00:46:03,440 --> 00:46:10,480
'I'm not asking you, Denton; I'm telling you to 
leave it alone for a couple of weeks. If you need  

482
00:46:10,480 --> 00:46:18,200
to go back to it later, of course you must. But 
I'm still the boss around here, remember?' ***

483
00:46:19,920 --> 00:46:25,520
Gavin stayed near Voyles's office until the 
secretary let him in. He couldn't believe it  

484
00:46:25,520 --> 00:46:30,000
when Voyles and Lewis told him that they were 
no longer investigating the Pelican theory.

485
00:46:32,560 --> 00:46:38,800
'My best friend is dead because of that 
brief,' he said. 'He was killed by a car bomb.  

486
00:46:39,680 --> 00:46:41,840
Someone is worried about 
the brief, don't you think?'

487
00:46:43,200 --> 00:46:47,840
'The brief has already been very 
valuable to us, Gavin,' Lewis said.

488
00:46:48,640 --> 00:46:53,680
'Yeah, it let you play some games with 
the White House,' Gavin said bitterly.  

489
00:46:54,400 --> 00:46:59,960
'But there's a girl out there running for 
her life. What am I going to tell her?' ***

490
00:47:01,520 --> 00:47:05,440
Darby made sure she could not be followed 
in the crowds in the shopping district.  

491
00:47:06,400 --> 00:47:12,720
She bought some new clothes and hid her hair 
under a hat. She went into the Sheraton Hotel  

492
00:47:12,720 --> 00:47:19,680
and found a row of pay phones. First she called 
Mrs Chen, who lived in the apartment next to hers:  

493
00:47:20,880 --> 00:47:27,440
no, she had not seen anything; yes, there had 
been a knock at her door early this morning.  

494
00:47:28,880 --> 00:47:30,080
Then she called Gavin.

495
00:47:32,160 --> 00:47:34,240
'Where are you?' he asked.

496
00:47:35,360 --> 00:47:41,840
'Let me explain something. For now, I'm not going 
to tell you or anyone else where I am. Clear?'

497
00:47:42,960 --> 00:47:44,480
'Yes, but don't go home.'

498
00:47:45,440 --> 00:47:52,080
'I'm not a fool. They've already 
been there. What did Mr Voyles say?'

499
00:47:52,080 --> 00:47:53,760
'I haven't been able to see him.'

500
00:47:54,800 --> 00:47:59,920
'You've been at the office for four hours, 
Gavin. I expected you to do better.'

501
00:48:01,120 --> 00:48:02,320
'Be patient, Darby.'

502
00:48:03,120 --> 00:48:07,040
'Patience will get me killed. 
I've got to keep moving.'

503
00:48:08,480 --> 00:48:13,360
She saw a face. He walked among the 
tourists at the hotel's front desk.  

504
00:48:14,320 --> 00:48:18,320
He was trying to look as though he 
belonged here, but his eyes were searching.  

505
00:48:19,440 --> 00:48:25,920
The face was long and thin, and he wore round 
glasses. He was a little over six feet tall.

506
00:48:27,040 --> 00:48:29,280
'Gavin, listen to me,' she said.  

507
00:48:30,160 --> 00:48:34,560
'I have to go. I can see a man I've 
seen before, about an hour ago.'

508
00:48:35,680 --> 00:48:39,360
'OK. Take care, Darby, and call me again soon.'

509
00:48:40,400 --> 00:48:40,960
'I'll try.'
 
 
 
 
 

510
00:48:45,280 --> 00:48:46,000
CHAPTER EIGHT

511
00:48:46,960 --> 00:48:48,800
Photos and Phone Calls
 

512
00:48:50,560 --> 00:48:57,520
The photographer's name was Croft. He was parked 
on Pennsylvania Avenue in Grantham's Volvo,  

513
00:48:57,520 --> 00:49:04,320
because it had a phone. The pay phone was easy 
to see, about fifty yards in front of the car.  

514
00:49:05,440 --> 00:49:09,280
With his powerful camera he could 
almost read the names in the phone book.  

515
00:49:10,560 --> 00:49:12,880
A large woman was using the phone at the moment.

516
00:49:14,400 --> 00:49:20,640
At 12:20 the woman put the phone down 
and walked away. From nowhere a young  

517
00:49:20,640 --> 00:49:26,720
man in a suit appeared and walked over to the 
phone. Croft felt sure that this was the man.  

518
00:49:28,560 --> 00:49:33,920
He picked up his camera and looked through 
it. The man was pushing numbers on the phone  

519
00:49:33,920 --> 00:49:40,720
and looked nervous. He kept looking this way 
and that. Croft took a couple of pictures.

520
00:49:42,000 --> 00:49:49,360
The phone in the car went three times. Croft 
didn't pick it up. It was Grantham at the office,  

521
00:49:49,920 --> 00:49:56,080
signalling that this was their man. Croft 
used a whole film on the first camera.  

522
00:49:57,280 --> 00:50:01,840
When the man had finished talking on the 
phone, he walked straight towards the Volvo  

523
00:50:01,840 --> 00:50:08,880
along the pavement. Beautiful. Croft took 
several more pictures with a second camera  

524
00:50:08,880 --> 00:50:14,640
and stopped well before the man could 
possibly see inside the car. An easy job.

525
00:50:16,520 --> 00:50:17,520
***

526
00:50:17,520 --> 00:50:23,840
Grantham got plenty of excellent pictures from 
Croft. Garcia didn't look Spanish, despite the  

527
00:50:23,840 --> 00:50:29,280
name he had chosen. He looked like thousands 
of other young lawyers up and down the country.

528
00:50:30,640 --> 00:50:32,720
From Garcia he got nothing.  

529
00:50:33,680 --> 00:50:40,880
It didn't matter. He let him talk about his wife 
and child, and how frightened he was. One day,  

530
00:50:40,880 --> 00:50:46,080
and one day soon, Garcia would give 
him the information, whatever it was.

531
00:50:47,760 --> 00:50:53,760
From Sarge he got a copy of a White House 
document naming Khamel as the probable killer  

532
00:50:53,760 --> 00:51:00,640
of Rosenberg and Jensen. This was good. There 
was little in the office files about Khamel,  

533
00:51:01,280 --> 00:51:07,040
and only two pictures, which looked like two 
different people, but he wrote it up into  

534
00:51:07,040 --> 00:51:12,320
a story and they decided to use both pictures 
and the story on the front page the next day.

535
00:51:14,200 --> 00:51:15,200
***

536
00:51:15,200 --> 00:51:20,880
The phone was going. After twenty-four hours 
on the run, she had drunk a bottle of wine  

537
00:51:20,880 --> 00:51:24,880
the night before and fallen asleep 
on her bed in the Marriott Hotel.  

538
00:51:26,240 --> 00:51:32,800
But first she had cut off her long red hair and 
coloured it black; they would be expecting blonde.  

539
00:51:33,680 --> 00:51:39,040
They would also be expecting her to run 
away, so despite her fears she stayed in New  

540
00:51:39,040 --> 00:51:45,280
Orleans. They would be watching all the police 
stations, so she had stayed away from them.

541
00:51:46,800 --> 00:51:53,760
The phone was still going. She picked 
it up and heard 'Darby? This is Gavin.'

542
00:51:54,800 --> 00:51:57,840
Now she was awake. 'How did you find me?'

543
00:51:58,960 --> 00:52:01,680
'We are the FBI. We have our ways.'

544
00:52:02,800 --> 00:52:09,920
'Wait. Let me think. Of course, you can trace 
me when I use my cards to pay for things.  

545
00:52:10,720 --> 00:52:18,240
How stupid of me! But if you can find me, they can 
find me too. They could be outside the door now.'

546
00:52:19,360 --> 00:52:25,040
'Stay in small hotels, then, 
and pay with cash. Now, listen.  

547
00:52:26,000 --> 00:52:30,080
I'm coming to New Orleans; 
it's Thomas's funeral tomorrow.

548
00:52:30,960 --> 00:52:34,880
'I think we should meet tonight. 
You have to trust me, Darby.'

549
00:52:35,840 --> 00:52:36,800
'What did Voyles say?'

550
00:52:37,840 --> 00:52:41,520
Gavin hesitated. 'We're taking 
no action at this time.'

551
00:52:42,240 --> 00:52:45,840
'That's lawyer talk, Gavin. What does it mean?'

552
00:52:46,480 --> 00:52:50,000
'I don't want to talk on the 
phone. That's why we have to meet.'

553
00:52:50,800 --> 00:52:54,480
'No. Tell me why Voyles is 
doing nothing about this.'

554
00:52:55,920 --> 00:52:58,480
'I'm not sure why. Honestly.'

555
00:52:59,600 --> 00:53:03,680
'What do you think, Gavin? Do you think 
Thomas was killed because of the brief?

556
00:53:05,120 --> 00:53:05,440
'Yes.'

557
00:53:06,560 --> 00:53:13,360
'Thanks. If Thomas was murdered because of the 
brief, then we know who killed him. And if we  

558
00:53:13,360 --> 00:53:19,120
know who killed Thomas, then we know who 
killed Rosenberg and Jensen. Am I right?'

559
00:53:20,240 --> 00:53:20,880
'Probably.'

560
00:53:21,920 --> 00:53:26,400
'That's good enough - "probably" 
means "yes" when a lawyer says it.  

561
00:53:27,120 --> 00:53:30,080
But the FBI is still doing 
nothing about my suspect.'

562
00:53:30,880 --> 00:53:36,720
'Calm down, Darby. Let's meet tonight and 
talk about this. I could save your life.'

563
00:53:38,800 --> 00:53:44,240
She carefully put the receiver of the phone under 
the pillow. She threw her things into a bag and  

564
00:53:44,240 --> 00:53:50,720
left the room. She walked up two floors to the 
seventeenth, then took the lift down to the tenth.  

565
00:53:51,920 --> 00:53:54,240
Then she walked down the 
stairs to the ground floor.  

566
00:53:55,520 --> 00:53:59,680
She hid in the women's room for half 
an hour, and then left the hotel.

567
00:54:01,760 --> 00:54:06,080
On Dumaine Street, in the French 
Quarter, she found an empty cafe  

568
00:54:06,080 --> 00:54:09,520
with a phone at the back. She called Verheek.

569
00:54:11,600 --> 00:54:14,160
'Where will you stay tonight?' she asked him.

570
00:54:14,960 --> 00:54:15,840
'At the Hilton.'

571
00:54:17,200 --> 00:54:20,240
'I'll call late tonight or early in the morning.'

572
00:54:21,680 --> 00:54:25,600
'Can you get the Washington Post down 
there? You should read it today.'

573
00:54:27,040 --> 00:54:29,600
'I can't wait. I'll speak to you later.'

574
00:54:31,680 --> 00:54:34,320
She bought a Post and read it at another cafe.  

575
00:54:35,600 --> 00:54:42,160
If the report was right, it fitted in 
with her theory. The local paper had  

576
00:54:42,160 --> 00:54:46,400
a picture of Thomas on the second page, 
with a long story about the explosion.  

577
00:54:47,600 --> 00:54:52,480
The police were looking for a white female whom 
several witnesses had seen there at the time.  

578
00:54:54,240 --> 00:55:01,280
She looked slowly at the photo of Thomas. 
He was so handsome. Tears filled her eyes.

579
00:55:02,840 --> 00:55:03,840
***

580
00:55:03,840 --> 00:55:09,200
Alice Stark, Darby's best friend, got 
the key to the apartment from Mrs Chen  

581
00:55:09,200 --> 00:55:15,120
and let herself in. She had been there plenty of 
times before, and everything looked all right.  

582
00:55:15,840 --> 00:55:21,920
Nothing was out of place; the whole apartment 
was tidy. The kitchen smelled of stale food.

583
00:55:23,360 --> 00:55:27,760
It was dark when she got there, but Darby 
had told her not to switch on the lights,  

584
00:55:28,320 --> 00:55:33,840
and certainly not to open the curtains. 
She used a torch to see her way around.

585
00:55:35,440 --> 00:55:37,840
She sat down at the computer and turned it on.  

586
00:55:39,040 --> 00:55:42,880
She looked for the files Darby had 
mentioned, but they weren't there.  

587
00:55:45,120 --> 00:55:50,640
By the light of the torch she looked in 
the boxes of diskettes; they were empty.

588
00:55:52,240 --> 00:55:57,280
Alice returned the key to Mrs Chen and walked 
half a mile to where she had left her car.  

589
00:55:58,640 --> 00:56:03,360
She met Darby as arranged in the restaurant, 
and she told her what she had discovered.  

590
00:56:04,880 --> 00:56:09,600
Darby did not seem surprised, and 
refused to answer Alice's questions.

591
00:56:12,280 --> 00:56:13,280
***

592
00:56:13,280 --> 00:56:17,200
Verheek was angry. She had 
said she would call him.  

593
00:56:18,400 --> 00:56:23,920
Now it was midnight and she still hadn't 
called. He could save her life if she called.  

594
00:56:25,600 --> 00:56:32,400
He had to do something. He decided to visit a 
few student bars to find out if anyone knew her  

595
00:56:32,400 --> 00:56:37,360
and had seen her recently. He got back 
to his room at three in the morning.  

596
00:56:38,240 --> 00:56:43,840
There were no messages. She hadn't 
called. Was she still alive?
 
 
 
 
 

597
00:56:47,920 --> 00:56:48,720
CHAPTER NINE

598
00:56:49,520 --> 00:56:50,720
Searching for Darby
 

599
00:56:53,040 --> 00:57:00,480
Another phone call from Garcia. The man still 
wouldn't talk. Why was he calling him before dawn  

600
00:57:00,480 --> 00:57:07,520
on a Saturday? They'd had the same conversation 
every time - that he had to think about the safety  

601
00:57:07,520 --> 00:57:13,920
of his wife and child, that he had seen something 
in his office - but there was never anything new.

602
00:57:15,600 --> 00:57:19,040
Grantham had just gone back to 
sleep when the phone went again.

603
00:57:20,720 --> 00:57:25,840
'Hello?' It was not Garcia this 
time; it was a female voice.  

604
00:57:27,680 --> 00:57:33,200
'Is this Gray Grantham of the Washington Post? 
He must get an unlisted telephone number.

605
00:57:34,880 --> 00:57:36,800
'It is. And who are you?'

606
00:57:38,560 --> 00:57:41,200
'Are you still on the story 
about Rosenberg and Jensen?'

607
00:57:42,000 --> 00:57:42,320
'Yes.'

608
00:57:43,280 --> 00:57:44,880
'Have you heard of the Pelican Brief?'

609
00:57:45,760 --> 00:57:48,960
'The Pelican Brief. No. What is it?'

610
00:57:50,160 --> 00:57:56,240
'It contains a theory about who killed the 
judges. It was given to the FBI last Monday  

611
00:57:56,240 --> 00:58:02,880
by a man called Thomas Callahan. Suddenly, on 
Wednesday, Callahan is killed by a car bomb.'

612
00:58:04,240 --> 00:58:05,360
'How do you know all this?'

613
00:58:06,800 --> 00:58:07,840
'I wrote the brief.'

614
00:58:09,120 --> 00:58:12,880
He was wide awake now, 
listening hard. 'Where are you?'

615
00:58:14,080 --> 00:58:14,800
'New Orleans.'

616
00:58:15,680 --> 00:58:16,640
'Are you in danger?'

617
00:58:17,760 --> 00:58:22,400
'I think so. But I'm OK for 
now. I'll call you again soon.  

618
00:58:23,280 --> 00:58:25,360
See if you can find out anything about the brief.'

619
00:58:26,600 --> 00:58:27,600
***

620
00:58:27,600 --> 00:58:33,760
She came early to Thomas's funeral, and 
she would stay late. She found an empty  

621
00:58:33,760 --> 00:58:38,320
room on the third floor of a student building 
that looked out over the university church.  

622
00:58:39,680 --> 00:58:46,080
She sat with her face to the window and saw 
his parents and brother arrive. Students and  

623
00:58:46,080 --> 00:58:50,800
staff came in twos and threes. She 
pressed a handkerchief to her eyes.

624
00:58:52,400 --> 00:58:56,640
Then she saw him: it was the 
thin-faced man with glasses!  

625
00:58:57,520 --> 00:59:03,840
He was wearing a coat and tie. He walked towards 
the church, looking carefully in every direction.  

626
00:59:05,200 --> 00:59:08,560
First they kill him, then 
they come to his funeral.

627
00:59:10,320 --> 00:59:18,000
Ten minutes later he came back out of the church. 
He looked sad, as if Thomas had been a friend.  

628
00:59:18,000 --> 00:59:22,320
He put a cigarette in his mouth and walked 
past some parked cars and behind the church.  

629
00:59:23,680 --> 00:59:29,600
Two minutes later, another man got out of one 
of the cars and followed him. The two of them  

630
00:59:29,600 --> 00:59:36,320
reappeared after a minute, walking together now. 
Then Thin-face disappeared down the street while  

631
00:59:36,320 --> 00:59:41,760
the other man, who was short, returned to his 
car and waited for the funeral service to finish.

632
00:59:44,440 --> 00:59:45,440
***

633
00:59:45,440 --> 00:59:50,800
The Cubans lowered the small rubber boat 
into the water from their ship. They heard  

634
00:59:50,800 --> 00:59:55,680
the sound of the little engine as the man went 
west through the darkness towards the coast.

635
00:59:57,360 --> 01:00:03,840
He would never use a commercial airline again; 
the photographs in Paris were embarrassing for a  

636
01:00:03,840 --> 01:00:11,200
professional like himself, and his client was not 
pleased. Now he was going to have to do two jobs  

637
01:00:11,200 --> 01:00:19,440
in a single month, which he had never done before. 
But this one would be easy - just a young woman.

638
01:00:21,360 --> 01:00:27,840
In the hotel room in New Orleans, he spoke on 
the phone to a man calling himself Mr Snellen

639
01:00:28,720 --> 01:00:30,880
'Tell me about her,' he said.

640
01:00:32,640 --> 01:00:34,640
'There are two photos in the briefcase.'

641
01:00:36,160 --> 01:00:38,880
Khamel opened the case and took out the photos.  

642
01:00:40,080 --> 01:00:45,520
'I've got them. She's beautiful. It 
will almost be a pity to kill her.'

643
01:00:46,640 --> 01:00:49,280
'Yes. But all that red hair has gone.  

644
01:00:50,080 --> 01:00:53,840
We found some hair on the floor of a 
hotel room. She has coloured it black.'

645
01:00:54,960 --> 01:00:55,840
'Where is she now?'

646
01:00:57,040 --> 01:01:01,040
'We don't know. She has stopped 
using her cards to pay for things.  

647
01:01:01,760 --> 01:01:07,040
She took out a lot of money from her bank, and 
since then she has disappeared. We think she's  

648
01:01:07,040 --> 01:01:12,880
still in New Orleans, though. Someone was in 
her apartment last night. We just missed them.

649
01:01:14,000 --> 01:01:18,640
'The bomb failed. We don't expect you to fail.'

650
01:01:20,280 --> 01:01:21,280
***

651
01:01:21,280 --> 01:01:25,760
Gavin was tired. He had spent 
two nights searching the bars,  

652
01:01:26,400 --> 01:01:31,520
and he was too old for these late nights. 
When the phone went, he was still asleep.

653
01:01:33,200 --> 01:01:33,600
'Gavin?'

654
01:01:34,560 --> 01:01:35,840
'Darby, is that you?'

655
01:01:36,800 --> 01:01:37,920
'Yes.'

656
01:01:37,920 --> 01:01:39,360
'Why haven't you called before?'

657
01:01:40,320 --> 01:01:45,920
'That doesn't matter now. You should know that 
they're here, in New Orleans. I've seen two  

658
01:01:45,920 --> 01:01:51,840
of them - a thin-faced man and a short man. 
They were at the funeral service yesterday.'

659
01:01:52,800 --> 01:01:53,440
'Where were you?'

660
01:01:54,400 --> 01:01:57,360
'Watching. How long will you be in town?'

661
01:01:58,320 --> 01:02:00,560
'Until we meet. When will that be?'

662
01:02:01,600 --> 01:02:04,240
'I don't know yet. I'll call again soon.'

663
01:02:05,520 --> 01:02:10,080
The phone went dead. Gavin picked it up 
and threw it across his hotel room.
 
 
 
 
 

664
01:02:14,240 --> 01:02:14,960
CHAPTER TEN

665
01:02:15,840 --> 01:02:16,640
Another Body
 

666
01:02:18,480 --> 01:02:24,640
The first thing she did when she woke up on 
Sunday morning was listen. Was the door opening?  

667
01:02:25,360 --> 01:02:32,240
Was the floor outside making a noise? When she 
was sure she was safe, she thought about Thomas.  

668
01:02:33,360 --> 01:02:37,440
She remembered their times together; 
she remembered how he loved her.  

669
01:02:38,800 --> 01:02:44,800
It was a surprise for him, the first time he 
had really been in love. And she loved him too.

670
01:02:46,720 --> 01:02:52,320
After a few minutes of thinking about 
Thomas, she thought about them. She  

671
01:02:52,320 --> 01:02:59,520
had to think like them too, to stay alive. 
Where would they be today? Where could she  

672
01:02:59,520 --> 01:03:06,720
go? Was it time to move hotels again? Yes. 
Did they know that she was now a blonde?

673
01:03:08,400 --> 01:03:16,400
She felt hungry. She had hardly eaten for days. 
This hotel didn't do breakfast on Sundays,  

674
01:03:16,400 --> 01:03:20,800
so she had to go out. She left by 
the back door, through the kitchen.

675
01:03:22,400 --> 01:03:24,720
He saw her when she reached Burgundy Street.  

676
01:03:25,600 --> 01:03:31,200
The hair was different, but she couldn't 
change her long legs. He started to follow her.

677
01:03:32,120 --> 01:03:33,120
***

678
01:03:33,120 --> 01:03:35,760
Khamel was practising his 
English when the phone went.  

679
01:03:36,560 --> 01:03:42,640
It was Sneller. 'She's here,' he said. 
'One of our men saw her this morning.  

680
01:03:43,200 --> 01:03:47,440
He chased her, but she noticed him 
and lost him in the football crowds.'

681
01:03:48,480 --> 01:03:54,880
Khamel said, 'So how am I supposed to find her, 
if your men can't tell me where she's staying?'

682
01:03:56,080 --> 01:04:00,720
'It might not matter,' Sneller said. 
'There's an FBI lawyer in town.  

683
01:04:01,360 --> 01:04:05,120
The fool has been visiting bars 
and asking questions about her,  

684
01:04:05,120 --> 01:04:11,840
spreading his name around. He's asked anyone who 
knows her to contact him at his hotel, the Hilton.  

685
01:04:12,720 --> 01:04:17,920
My men will continue trying to find the 
girl, and you can stay close to him. He's in

686
01:04:17,920 --> 01:04:25,840
'Room 1909. He was Callahan's 
best friend. She might call him.'

687
01:04:25,840 --> 01:04:26,000
***

688
01:04:26,000 --> 01:04:31,760
Gavin was lying on his bed, watching 
TV. It was eleven at night. He would  

689
01:04:31,760 --> 01:04:37,760
wait until twelve and then try to sleep. He had 
decided to go home tomorrow if she didn't call.  

690
01:04:38,880 --> 01:04:45,040
He couldn't find her. It wasn't his fault: 
even taxi-drivers got lost in this city.

691
01:04:46,800 --> 01:04:50,080
When the phone went, he switched 
the TV off and picked it up.

692
01:04:52,080 --> 01:04:53,840
'It's me, Gavin,' she said.

693
01:04:54,640 --> 01:04:56,480
'You're alive,' he said.

694
01:04:57,120 --> 01:05:00,800
'Yes, but I was followed 
today. It was the short man.'

695
01:05:01,840 --> 01:05:03,600
'Did he follow you from somewhere?'

696
01:05:04,560 --> 01:05:08,160
No, he just happened to see me in the streets.'

697
01:05:08,160 --> 01:05:14,640
'Listen, Darby, I can't wait here any more. 
I've got a job to go back to. I want to leave  

698
01:05:14,640 --> 01:05:20,160
New Orleans tomorrow, and I want you to come 
with me. I'll have three men guarding you,  

699
01:05:20,160 --> 01:05:25,520
and you'll be safe. You can tell us all you 
know, and then the FBI will finish the job.'

700
01:05:26,800 --> 01:05:29,840
Darby thought for a minute. 'All right.  

701
01:05:30,880 --> 01:05:34,560
Behind your hotel there's a 
shopping area called Riverwalk.'

702
01:05:35,520 --> 01:05:36,160
'I know it.'

703
01:05:36,960 --> 01:05:43,600
'Good. Find a shop called Frenchmen's Bend and 
be there, at the back of the shop, at midday  

704
01:05:43,600 --> 01:05:49,840
tomorrow. I don't know what you look like, 
so wear a black shirt and carry a newspaper.'

705
01:05:50,720 --> 01:05:51,600
'This is silly.'

706
01:05:52,320 --> 01:05:59,120
'No, it's not. I've had to learn fast how to stay 
alive. Believe me, this is the way to do it.'

707
01:06:00,320 --> 01:06:02,000
'OK, you're the boss.'

708
01:06:02,800 --> 01:06:06,400
'That's right. Only you and I will leave the city.  

709
01:06:07,040 --> 01:06:10,160
I don't want anyone else knowing 
about this. Do you understand?'

710
01:06:11,120 --> 01:06:11,680
'All right.'

711
01:06:12,720 --> 01:06:13,600
'How tall are you?'

712
01:06:14,480 --> 01:06:16,720
'About five feet, ten inches.'

713
01:06:17,520 --> 01:06:18,560
'And how much to you weigh?'

714
01:06:19,520 --> 01:06:25,200
'About a hundred kilos. I usually lie about 
it. I'm going to start doing some exercise.'

715
01:06:26,160 --> 01:06:27,520
'I'll see you tomorrow, Gavin.'

716
01:06:28,640 --> 01:06:29,280
'I hope so.'

717
01:06:30,960 --> 01:06:36,960
He put the phone down and smiled. 
'Great! At last!' he said out loud.  

718
01:06:38,160 --> 01:06:40,000
He went into the bathroom for a shower.

719
01:06:40,880 --> 01:06:48,160
When he came out, the room was dark. Dark? 
But he had left the light on, hadn't he?  

720
01:06:49,520 --> 01:06:51,520
He started to walk over to the light switch.

721
01:06:52,640 --> 01:06:56,480
The first blow caught him in the 
throat. He fell to his knees,  

722
01:06:56,480 --> 01:07:03,600
which made the second blow easy. It landed like a 
rock on the back of his neck, and Gavin was dead.

723
01:07:04,800 --> 01:07:09,680
Khamel switched on a light. He lifted 
up the body and put it on the bed.  

724
01:07:10,960 --> 01:07:15,200
He turned the sound on the 
television up loud, opened his bag  

725
01:07:15,200 --> 01:07:21,440
and took out a cheap gun. He held it to 
the right side of Gavin's head and fired.  

726
01:07:22,560 --> 01:07:27,840
Then he carefully put the gun in Gavin's 
right hand and curled the fingers around it.  

727
01:07:28,800 --> 01:07:32,480
It wouldn't take a doctor very long 
to find out how Gavin had really died,  

728
01:07:33,120 --> 01:07:39,600
but Khamel didn't need very long -by the evening 
of the next day he would be out of the country.

729
01:07:41,200 --> 01:07:45,280
He opened up the receiver of the telephone 
and took out the little microphone.  

730
01:07:46,320 --> 01:07:48,480
He pulled the recorder out from under the bed.  

731
01:07:49,600 --> 01:07:53,200
Finally, he checked that the cupboard 
where he had waited was clean.  

732
01:07:54,560 --> 01:08:01,520
Then he left the room. No one had seen 
him enter, and no one saw him leave.
 
 
 
 
 

733
01:08:12,480 --> 01:08:13,280
CHAPTER ELEVEN

734
01:08:14,080 --> 01:08:14,800
Riverwalk
 

735
01:08:17,040 --> 01:08:22,240
Grantham couldn't find out anything about 
the brief. Even Sarge hadn't heard of it.  

736
01:08:23,440 --> 01:08:28,640
When Darby's call came through to his office 
on Monday morning he had nothing to tell her.

737
01:08:30,160 --> 01:08:36,400
'It doesn't matter. I'll tell you everything 
soon, I think. I don't want to die without  

738
01:08:36,400 --> 01:08:40,800
telling the world what I know. They're 
following me here in New Orleans.'

739
01:08:41,760 --> 01:08:42,080
'Who?'

740
01:08:42,960 --> 01:08:49,040
'The same people who killed Rosenberg and Jensen. 
If you've read the report about Callahan's death,  

741
01:08:49,600 --> 01:08:57,520
you know about the white female the police want to 
talk to. That's me. My name is Darby Shaw. Thomas  

742
01:08:57,520 --> 01:09:05,920
Callahan was my teacher and my lover. I wrote the 
brief, gave it to him, he passed it on to the FBI,  

743
01:09:05,920 --> 01:09:11,840
who took it to the White House, and you know 
what happened next. Are you recording this?'

744
01:09:12,960 --> 01:09:15,600
'I'm writing it down,' Grantham said.

745
01:09:16,480 --> 01:09:22,640
'I'm going to leave New Orleans. I'll call you 
from somewhere else tomorrow. Can you get a copy  

746
01:09:22,640 --> 01:09:26,880
of the list of people who gave large amounts 
of money to help the President get elected?'

747
01:09:28,320 --> 01:09:32,400
'Easy; it's public information. 
I'll have it by the time you call.

748
01:09:33,520 --> 01:09:34,960
'Do you have a copy of the brief?'

749
01:09:36,000 --> 01:09:37,840
'No, but I remember it all.'

750
01:09:38,880 --> 01:09:40,560
'And you know who's doing the killing?'

751
01:09:41,600 --> 01:09:45,920
'Yes, and as soon as I tell you, 
your life will be in danger too.'

752
01:09:46,640 --> 01:09:48,240
'Tell me now.'

753
01:09:48,240 --> 01:09:51,120
'Not so fast. I'll call you tomorrow.'

754
01:09:53,360 --> 01:09:59,200
After the phone conversation Grantham went in 
to see his boss, Smith Keen. He explained the  

755
01:09:59,200 --> 01:10:06,880
situation to him. Keen was excited, but said, 
'Even if she tells us what's in the brief,  

756
01:10:06,880 --> 01:10:11,200
we can't print the story; we'll 
need an independent witness.'

757
01:10:12,720 --> 01:10:17,120
'I'm working on it,' Grantham 
said, and told him about Garcia.

758
01:10:18,320 --> 01:10:23,280
'This is going to be big,' Keen 
said. 'This is going to put the

759
01:10:23,280 --> 01:10:25,440
'Post right back up at the top.'

760
01:10:27,000 --> 01:10:28,000
***

761
01:10:28,000 --> 01:10:33,840
She arrived on Riverwalk at eleven. She sat 
in a restaurant and nervously drank a coffee  

762
01:10:33,840 --> 01:10:41,280
while watching the people pass. She didn't see 
Thin-face or Shorty or anyone else she recognized.  

763
01:10:42,640 --> 01:10:50,640
At 11:45 she got up and walked towards Frenchmen's 
Bend. If he wasn't there by 12:15 she would leave.  

764
01:10:51,920 --> 01:10:58,480
But he was there, wearing the black shirt and 
carrying a newspaper. He looked nervous too.  

765
01:10:59,440 --> 01:11:04,880
She liked that. At exactly twelve o'clock he 
walked into the shop and went to the back.

766
01:11:05,760 --> 01:11:08,640
She came up behind him and said, 'Gavin.'

767
01:11:10,240 --> 01:11:15,120
He had practised Gavin's voice for hours, 
but wasn't sure he had it exactly right.  

768
01:11:16,160 --> 01:11:22,880
He turned around quickly and said, 'Darby.' 
Then he pretended to cough. She wouldn't  

769
01:11:22,880 --> 01:11:28,640
expect the same voice from someone with 
a cold. 'Let's get out of here,' he said.

770
01:11:30,080 --> 01:11:36,080
'Follow me,' she said. Darby took his hand and 
led him out of the shop and towards the river.

771
01:11:37,760 --> 01:11:40,080
'Have you seen them?' he asked.

772
01:11:41,040 --> 01:11:43,040
'No, but they're around somewhere.'

773
01:11:44,160 --> 01:11:45,200
'Where are we going?'

774
01:11:46,480 --> 01:11:47,280
'Just come with me.'

775
01:11:48,400 --> 01:11:52,320
'You're walking too fast, Darby. 
It will look strange to people.  

776
01:11:53,120 --> 01:11:58,320
Let me make a phone call. I can have men 
here in ten minutes and then we'll be safe.'  

777
01:11:59,440 --> 01:12:02,720
He was pleased with himself; 
he sounded just right.

778
01:12:03,920 --> 01:12:12,480
'No,' she said, but she slowed down. They joined 
the queue for the riverboat Bayou Queen. 'The  

779
01:12:12,480 --> 01:12:18,240
boat will take us to where I've parked a car,' 
she explained. 'Then we get out of here fast.'

780
01:12:19,360 --> 01:12:24,640
Khamel was uncomfortable; he was wearing a 
great many un-derclothes, so that he would  

781
01:12:24,640 --> 01:12:32,640
look as fat as Verheek. But he could wait an hour 
until they were out of the city. And then . . .

782
01:12:32,640 --> 01:12:37,600
The man with the gun pushed his way 
through the queue. He had killed before,  

783
01:12:37,600 --> 01:12:44,640
but never in such a public place. The queue was 
moving, but he was getting through it. The man  

784
01:12:44,640 --> 01:12:50,080
and the woman were just about to step on to the 
boat when he reached them. He pulled the gun  

785
01:12:50,080 --> 01:12:57,120
out of his pocket, held it to the man's head 
and fired. He disappeared through the crowd.

786
01:12:58,960 --> 01:13:03,840
Gavin was falling to the ground. Darby 
screamed and moved back in horror.  

787
01:13:04,720 --> 01:13:10,800
'He's got a gun!' a woman shouted, and pointed 
at Gavin, who was on his hands and knees,  

788
01:13:10,800 --> 01:13:18,160
with a small gun in his right hand. Blood poured 
from his nose and chin, and formed a small pool  

789
01:13:18,160 --> 01:13:23,040
under his face. His head was hanging 
down until it nearly touched the ground.  

790
01:13:24,240 --> 01:13:27,840
He was speaking some words in a 
language Darby didn't recognize.

791
01:13:29,120 --> 01:13:31,840
'He's Egyptian,' someone in the crowd said.

792
01:13:33,040 --> 01:13:39,120
He fell forward, dropping the gun into the 
water, and died in a widening pool of blood.  

793
01:13:40,880 --> 01:13:45,920
Darby walked away as the crowd 
moved forwards to see the dead man,  

794
01:13:45,920 --> 01:13:48,400
and two policemen started 
to push their way through.

795
01:13:51,080 --> 01:13:52,080
***

796
01:13:52,080 --> 01:13:57,520
She left Riverwalk after dark. She had bought 
new clothes and wore a new coat as well.  

797
01:13:58,800 --> 01:14:00,080
She waved at a taxi.

798
01:14:02,400 --> 01:14:05,280
'How much to take me to Baton Rouge?' she asked.

799
01:14:06,160 --> 01:14:10,880
'That's a long way,' the driver said. 
'You should go by bus or train.'

800
01:14:12,080 --> 01:14:14,160
'How much?' she asked again.

801
01:14:15,120 --> 01:14:19,680
'One hundred and fifty dollars,' the 
man said, after a moment's thought.

802
01:14:20,800 --> 01:14:24,400
'Here's two hundred,' she 
said. 'Get me there fast.'  

803
01:14:25,840 --> 01:14:31,600
Thomas had talked to her about his friend Gavin 
Verheek. She knew he wasn't an Egyptian.
 
 
 
 
 

804
01:14:35,760 --> 01:14:36,560
CHAPTER TWELVE

805
01:14:37,440 --> 01:14:38,640
Darby Explains
 

806
01:14:40,480 --> 01:14:44,800
