01:15:02,080 --> 01:15:08,400
'I know,' Voyles said. 'We'll send down a team 
of men, but I don't want the fool in the White  

811
01:15:08,400 --> 01:15:14,880
House or Coal to hear that we're investigating 
it - I want to surprise them. When the President  

812
01:15:14,880 --> 01:15:19,920
told me to leave the brief alone, I was 
carrying a small recorder in my pocket.  

813
01:15:20,800 --> 01:15:27,200
I've got every word, loud and clear. 
If we find that the brief is accurate,  

814
01:15:27,200 --> 01:15:33,280
the press will love us, and we can let them know 
that the President told us not to investigate it.'

815
01:15:34,480 --> 01:15:38,240
'That'll be the end of him 
and Coal,' Lewis said happily.

816
01:15:38,960 --> 01:15:44,320
'I know. He'll have no chance in the 
election next year. We've got him.'

817
01:15:45,520 --> 01:15:52,160
They smiled at each other. 'But what about 
Mattiece?' Lewis said. 'If he hadn't killed  

818
01:15:52,160 --> 01:15:57,200
all -those people, we wouldn't have thought 
the brief was right. He must be crazy.'

819
01:15:58,240 --> 01:16:05,200
'There are rumours that he is,' Voyles 
replied. 'I've spoken to the CIA. They  

820
01:16:05,200 --> 01:16:11,600
had men in New Orleans. They don't know where 
Mattiece is. He's probably not in this country.  

821
01:16:12,240 --> 01:16:18,800
He owns houses all over the world. We'll need 
their help to get him. They were following the  

822
01:16:18,800 --> 01:16:24,240
girl too, but they lost her in Chicago 
airport. She could be anywhere by now.'

823
01:16:25,200 --> 01:16:31,240
'She could be dead,' Lewis said. 'Mattiece's 
men are following her as well.' ***

824
01:16:32,960 --> 01:16:38,240
Grantham traced two old photographs 
of her - one from her high school,  

825
01:16:38,240 --> 01:16:44,400
one from her first university. He pinned 
them up beside his desk. She was beautiful.

826
01:16:45,680 --> 01:16:51,360
She called him as she had promised. He had read 
about the killing of a lawyer in New Orleans,  

827
01:16:51,360 --> 01:16:56,960
and she told him the true story. She also 
told him about the other killing, which had  

828
01:16:56,960 --> 01:17:03,840
not appeared in the newspapers. Then she said, 
'Can you come to New York tomorrow, Grantham?'

829
01:17:04,880 --> 01:17:10,560
'Of course. It'll only take a few 
hours. But please call me Gray.'  

830
01:17:12,000 --> 01:17:13,520
He looked at the photographs of her.

831
01:17:14,560 --> 01:17:17,120
'I'll ring tomorrow morning 
to tell you where to meet me.  

832
01:17:17,680 --> 01:17:21,520
And tomorrow I'll tell you who 
killed Rosenberg and Jensen.'

833
01:17:22,960 --> 01:17:24,080
'Do you know who did it?'

834
01:17:25,520 --> 01:17:31,920
'I know who paid for the killings. I know his 
name. I know his business and his politics.'

835
01:17:33,040 --> 01:17:34,320
'And you'll tell me tomorrow.'

836
01:17:35,360 --> 01:17:36,400
'If I'm still alive.'

837
01:17:37,600 --> 01:17:44,880
A pause. 'Perhaps we should 
talk immediately,' he said. ***

838
01:17:44,880 --> 01:17:48,240
They met in her room in the 
St Moritz Hotel in New York.  

839
01:17:49,360 --> 01:17:51,600
They chatted for a while, 
getting to know each other.  

840
01:17:52,880 --> 01:18:00,160
It was the first normal conversation Darby had had 
for a week, and it was a great pleasure. They sent  

841
01:18:00,160 --> 01:18:06,560
out for some food, and after they had eaten he 
switched on a recorder and she told him a story:

842
01:18:08,640 --> 01:18:13,040
'For centuries, the Mississippi River 
has been carrying mud down to the sea.  

843
01:18:14,160 --> 01:18:18,800
Where the river meets the sea, marshes 
have spread out over an enormous area.  

844
01:18:19,840 --> 01:18:26,320
These marshes are the home for a great many rare 
and unusual animals, birds, reptiles and fish.'

845
01:18:27,760 --> 01:18:34,400
'Then oil was discovered there in 1930. The 
oil companies began to destroy the marshes.  

846
01:18:35,280 --> 01:18:40,720
Where the river mud had been creating new land, 
now the sea was able to wash the land away.  

847
01:18:42,160 --> 01:18:47,280
Since the discovery of oil, tens of thousands 
of acres of Louisiana marshland has gone.  

848
01:18:48,320 --> 01:18:51,920
Every fourteen minutes, another 
acre disappears under water.'

849
01:18:52,760 --> 01:19:01,440
'In 1979 an oil company owned by Victor Mattiece 
found a very rich oilfield, worth thousands of  

850
01:19:01,440 --> 01:19:08,560
millions of dollars. Mattiece wanted it all. 
He knew that others would buy the surrounding  

851
01:19:08,560 --> 01:19:13,680
land if they heard there was a major oilfield 
there, so he pretended that nothing had happened.  

852
01:19:14,880 --> 01:19:20,960
He stopped work there, and waited. Slowly 
and patiently, as the years passed,  

853
01:19:21,520 --> 01:19:27,600
he bought the surrounding land. He 
created new companies, lots of them,  

854
01:19:27,600 --> 01:19:33,840
so that no one would know that he was the 
buyer. At last he was ready to begin drilling.'

855
01:19:35,520 --> 01:19:42,720
'Then a small environmental group called Green 
Rescue made a legal request to the courts to stop  

856
01:19:42,720 --> 01:19:50,880
the drilling. The request was un-expected, because 
for so long Louisiana had profited from the oil  

857
01:19:50,880 --> 01:19:57,840
companies. The court in Lafayette agreed that all 
drilling should stop until the case was settled.'

858
01:19:59,760 --> 01:20:06,240
'Mattiece knew that this could take 
years. He was dangerously angry. He spent  

859
01:20:06,240 --> 01:20:12,560
weeks with his lawyers, making plans. But every 
move they made was disallowed by the courts.'

860
01:20:14,160 --> 01:20:19,520
'People were sympathetic to Green Rescue's 
case. A lot of wildlife was at risk.  

861
01:20:20,720 --> 01:20:25,600
The marshland where Mattiece wanted to 
drill was home to a great many rare and  

862
01:20:25,600 --> 01:20:32,400
beautiful sea birds, including brown pelicans. 
There were very few of these pelicans left.  

863
01:20:33,840 --> 01:20:37,680
When people thought about the case, 
they thought about the pelicans.'

864
01:20:39,200 --> 01:20:45,840
'At last the case came to trial. Green 
Rescue lost, and that was not surprising:  

865
01:20:46,880 --> 01:20:51,440
Mattiece had spent millions of dollars 
and had the best lawyers in the country.  

866
01:20:52,480 --> 01:20:55,920
But the judge still forbade the drilling to start.  

867
01:20:57,040 --> 01:21:03,120
The pelican was a protected bird under Louisiana 
law, and Green Rescue weren't finished yet:  

868
01:21:04,480 --> 01:21:07,920
they would take the case all 
the way to the Supreme Court.'

869
01:21:09,520 --> 01:21:13,840
'How long would it take to reach 
the Supreme Court?' Gray asked.

870
01:21:14,880 --> 01:21:17,040
'Between three and five years.'

871
01:21:18,400 --> 01:21:20,720
'By then Rosenberg would be dead anyway.'

872
01:21:21,760 --> 01:21:27,840
'Yes, but it might be a Democratic President 
who was choosing the judge to take his place;  

873
01:21:28,800 --> 01:21:34,880
Mattiece couldn't take that chance. And 
Jensen was always soft on environmental cases.  

874
01:21:36,080 --> 01:21:42,640
Mattiece needed two Republican judges in there, 
both of whom were supporters of big business.'

875
01:21:43,920 --> 01:21:47,360
'Can you prove that all the 
companies involved in buying  

876
01:21:47,360 --> 01:21:50,400
the land in Louisiana are owned by Mattiece?'

877
01:21:51,680 --> 01:21:57,600
'It's in the brief, and I've written it all 
out for you. And then there's the photograph.'

878
01:21:58,720 --> 01:21:59,200
'Tell me.'

879
01:22:00,720 --> 01:22:06,800
'Seven years ago, before the President was 
elected, he was in New Orleans getting money  

880
01:22:06,800 --> 01:22:13,520
for the Republicans. Although Mattiece stays 
out of the public eye, he was there that day,  

881
01:22:14,480 --> 01:22:19,440
and some clever photographer got a picture 
of him shaking hands with the President.  

882
01:22:20,560 --> 01:22:25,920
Both of them are smiling, and they 
look like old friends. It's beautiful.'

883
01:22:27,040 --> 01:22:34,080
'I can easily find a copy of that. This whole 
thing is beautiful. It's the biggest story since  

884
01:22:34,080 --> 01:22:41,600
Watergate - maybe even bigger.' Gray turned 
off the recorder and sat back in his chair.  

885
01:22:42,400 --> 01:22:46,080
They were silent for a short while. Then he asked,  

886
01:22:47,360 --> 01:22:52,320
'Do you think Mattiece himself 
chose Rosenberg and Jensen?'

887
01:22:52,320 --> 01:22:58,960
'No, I'm sure he had advice from a lawyer. 
He's got lawyers all over the country.'

888
01:23:00,240 --> 01:23:04,320
Gray sat up again. 'Does 
he have any in Washington?'

889
01:23:05,520 --> 01:23:13,120
'Yes, there are two firms there who do some work 
for him - Brim, Stearns and Kidlow is one of them;  

890
01:23:13,680 --> 01:23:20,560
the other is White and Blazevich, a very old, 
Republican firm. But why are you interested?'

891
01:23:22,240 --> 01:23:29,040
Gray quickly told her about Garcia. 'Maybe 
he works at one of those two firms,' he said.  

892
01:23:29,760 --> 01:23:31,680
'That would make it much easier to find him.'

893
01:23:33,280 --> 01:23:38,720
They were both tired. She asked him to 
sleep on the sofa in her room that night,  

894
01:23:38,720 --> 01:23:42,080
so that she could get a good night's 
sleep for the first time for days.  

895
01:23:43,200 --> 01:23:48,160
He agreed. She was so beautiful that 
he would do anything to be close her;  

896
01:23:49,760 --> 01:23:52,160
he would even sleep on a five-foot sofa.
 
 
 
 
 

897
01:23:56,480 --> 01:23:57,440
CHAPTER THIRTEEN

898
01:23:58,640 --> 01:23:59,360
Washington
 

899
01:24:01,120 --> 01:24:05,360
Darby worked in the library all 
morning and rang Grantham at midday.  

900
01:24:06,720 --> 01:24:11,920
She had been reading lists of the members at both 
the Washington law firms that worked for Mattiece;  

901
01:24:12,880 --> 01:24:16,000
there was no one called Garcia 
on either list, of course.  

902
01:24:17,200 --> 01:24:23,200
There were four Spanish names among the 190 
lawyers who worked for Brim, Stearns and Kidlow,  

903
01:24:23,920 --> 01:24:29,920
but none among the 412 who 
worked for White and Blazevich.

904
01:24:29,920 --> 01:24:34,320
She rang Gray with this information from 
a pay phone in a cafe on Sixth Avenue.  

905
01:24:35,680 --> 01:24:40,960
As she turned to leave she saw the short man 
who had been looking for her in New Orleans.  

906
01:24:42,240 --> 01:24:50,560
He was here, in New York, walking the streets. 
He didn't look inside the cafe, however. For the  

907
01:24:50,560 --> 01:24:58,400
moment she was safe, but it was time to leave New 
York. Two hours later, she was at Newark airport.

908
01:24:59,680 --> 01:25:07,120
When this was all over - if she was still alive - 
where could she go? She thought of the thousands  

909
01:25:07,120 --> 01:25:14,240
of islands in the Caribbean; no one could find 
her there. She no longer wanted to practise law.  

910
01:25:15,040 --> 01:25:20,080
All she wanted to do was reach her twenty-fifth 
birthday, and maybe her thirtieth too.

911
01:25:21,800 --> 01:25:22,800
***

912
01:25:22,800 --> 01:25:27,120
Croft spent a week waiting outside the 
offices of Brim, Stearns and Kidlow.  

913
01:25:27,920 --> 01:25:31,200
There were plenty of lawyers 
who looked as young as Garcia,  

914
01:25:31,200 --> 01:25:39,840
and they all dressed similarly in dark suits, 
but there was no Garcia. He was sure of it.

915
01:25:39,840 --> 01:25:40,400
***

916
01:25:40,400 --> 01:25:45,040
Some of the people employed by the White 
House didn't work at the White House;  

917
01:25:46,080 --> 01:25:50,160
some were so secret that 
their offices were elsewhere  

918
01:25:50,160 --> 01:25:56,720
and very few people knew of their existence. 
Matthew Barr was one of these shadowy people.

919
01:25:58,160 --> 01:26:04,400
He was riding in the back of the car with Coal. 
Coal was silent while Barr read the Pelican Brief.  

920
01:26:05,840 --> 01:26:12,000
When he had finished, Barr said, 'I'd 
love to know how much of this is true.'

921
01:26:13,360 --> 01:26:15,520
'So would we,' Coal said.

922
01:26:16,720 --> 01:26:18,560
'What did the President say about it?'

923
01:26:19,680 --> 01:26:25,280
'He agreed that the theory was implausible, 
so he asked Voyles not to investigate it.'

924
01:26:26,400 --> 01:26:28,960
'Really? And what if it's true?'

925
01:26:30,240 --> 01:26:33,600
'Then the President has got problems. Me too.'

926
01:26:35,040 --> 01:26:38,400
They rode in silence for a 
while and watched the traffic.  

927
01:26:39,360 --> 01:26:43,280
Then Coal said, 'We need to 
know if the brief is true.'

928
01:26:44,720 --> 01:26:50,160
'If people are dying, it's true. Why 
else did Callahan and Verheek die?'

929
01:26:51,840 --> 01:26:57,600
There was no other reason, and Coal 
knew it. 'I want you to do something.'

930
01:26:58,720 --> 01:26:59,520
'Find the girl?'

931
01:27:00,560 --> 01:27:03,840
'No, go to Mattiece and talk to him.'

932
01:27:04,720 --> 01:27:08,800
'It won't be easy. He isn't 
exactly listed in the phone book.'

933
01:27:10,160 --> 01:27:17,920
'You can do it. You've done more difficult things 
for us in the past. You've done worse for us too.'

934
01:27:17,920 --> 01:27:21,600
'And you think Victor will trust 
me and tell me his secrets?'

935
01:27:22,720 --> 01:27:29,440
'Why not? You're not a policeman. You can help 
him; you can tell him that the press will have  

936
01:27:29,440 --> 01:27:35,600
the story soon and so it would be a good idea 
for him to disappear. Then he'll trust you.'

937
01:27:37,120 --> 01:27:40,560
'What if it's true? What will you do next?'

938
01:27:41,760 --> 01:27:46,880
'The first thing will be for the President to 
appoint two nature-lovers to the Supreme Court;  

939
01:27:47,840 --> 01:27:54,000
that will show people that we really care 
for the environment. Then, at the same time,  

940
01:27:54,800 --> 01:27:59,840
he will get the FBI to start an official 
investigation into Victor Mattiece.'

941
01:28:00,880 --> 01:28:06,720
Barr was smiling with admiration. 
'What about the photograph?' he asked.

942
01:28:07,680 --> 01:28:14,400
'Easy. It's seven years old. We say that 
in those days Mattiece was a good citizen,  

943
01:28:14,960 --> 01:28:18,720
not a madman as he is now. Anyway,  

944
01:28:18,720 --> 01:28:24,560
by Sunday I'll tell you where he is. I've 
got a man working on it. Be ready to leave.'

945
01:28:26,520 --> 01:28:27,520
***

946
01:28:27,520 --> 01:28:34,000
Darby called Gray at 9:30 the next morning 
at his office. 'I'm here,' she said.

947
01:28:35,520 --> 01:28:38,080
'Where are you calling from?' Gray asked.

948
01:28:39,120 --> 01:28:43,520
'I'm staying at the Tabard Inn. I 
saw an old friend in New York and  

949
01:28:43,520 --> 01:28:47,920
decided it was time to leave. I hope 
I didn't bring any of them with me.  

950
01:28:49,200 --> 01:28:55,120
I bought two plane tickets with my card, for them 
to follow, but I paid cash for the one I really  

951
01:28:55,120 --> 01:29:02,960
used. Even then I changed planes four times. 
If they follow me here, they must be magicians.  

952
01:29:03,920 --> 01:29:07,520
If I see any of them here, I 
think I'll just surrender.'

953
01:29:08,560 --> 01:29:09,840
'When do we meet?'

954
01:29:11,040 --> 01:29:16,880
'Meet me in the restaurant here at nine 
tonight. But, Gray, don't use your own car;  

955
01:29:17,520 --> 01:29:21,680
hire another one. And be ready 
to stay away from your home  

956
01:29:21,680 --> 01:29:26,640
and office for a few days. I've booked 
you a room at the Marbury Hotel.'

957
01:29:27,680 --> 01:29:29,760
'Surely the office is safe, Darby.'

958
01:29:30,800 --> 01:29:36,480
'I'm not in the mood to argue. If you're going 
to be difficult, Gray, I'll simply disappear.  

959
01:29:37,600 --> 01:29:44,240
I'm sure I'll live longer out of the country, 
anyway. I've got to go now. You be careful.'

960
01:29:45,720 --> 01:29:46,720
***

961
01:29:46,720 --> 01:29:50,800
The Marbury was close to where 
his boss, Smith Keen, lived,  

962
01:29:50,800 --> 01:29:56,960
and there were some things they had to talk 
about. The next morning he rang Keen from his  

963
01:29:56,960 --> 01:30:04,080
room and they arranged to meet outside the front 
of the hotel in fifteen minutes. While they drove  

964
01:30:04,080 --> 01:30:09,680
around in Keen's car they discussed various ways 
in which they could use the information they had.  

965
01:30:10,880 --> 01:30:14,560
They agreed that finding Garcia 
was the key to the whole story;  

966
01:30:15,600 --> 01:30:22,480
without Garcia they had little more than 
rumour and an unlikely theory. They hoped  

967
01:30:22,480 --> 01:30:26,880
that Garcia's information really was as 
important as they were guessing it was.

968
01:30:28,160 --> 01:30:31,440
She had told him to stay off the 
streets and to eat in his room.  

969
01:30:32,560 --> 01:30:37,680
After Keen had left him near his hotel, 
he bought a sandwich and a cup of coffee,  

970
01:30:37,680 --> 01:30:42,960
and returned to his room. An Asian cleaning 
woman was working outside his room.  

971
01:30:44,400 --> 01:30:51,600
'Did you forget something, sir?' she asked. 
Gray looked at her. 'What do you mean?'

972
01:30:52,800 --> 01:30:54,880
'You just left your room, 
sir, and now you're back.'

973
01:30:56,320 --> 01:30:57,520
'I left two hours ago.'

974
01:30:58,480 --> 01:31:05,040
'No, sir. A man left your room ten minutes ago.' 
She hesitated and looked at his face closely.  

975
01:31:06,080 --> 01:31:08,240
'But now I see that it was another man, sir.'

976
01:31:10,320 --> 01:31:16,000
He walked quickly to the stairs and ran 
all the way down to the ground floor.  

977
01:31:16,000 --> 01:31:23,040
What was in his room? Nothing important 
- just some clothes. Nothing about Darby.  

978
01:31:24,160 --> 01:31:26,880
Her phone number at the 
Tabard Inn was in his pocket.

979
01:31:28,160 --> 01:31:30,640
He had to find her, and quick.
 
 
 
 
 

980
01:31:34,960 --> 01:31:35,840
CHAPTER FOURTEEN

981
01:31:36,960 --> 01:31:38,480
Curtis D. Morgan
 

982
01:31:40,320 --> 01:31:46,000
Darby spent the day in the Georgetown law library, 
reading and taking notes about the members of the  

983
01:31:46,000 --> 01:31:52,720
Washington law firms that Mattiece used. It 
was boring work, and her mind often wandered.

984
01:31:53,760 --> 01:31:55,360
She thought a lot about Thomas.

985
01:31:56,280 --> 01:31:57,280
***

986
01:31:57,280 --> 01:32:00,480
Matthew Barr went to New 
Orleans, where he met a lawyer  

987
01:32:00,480 --> 01:32:04,560
who told him to fly to a certain 
hotel in Fort Lauderdale, Florida.

988
01:32:06,000 --> 01:32:10,640
He wouldn't tell Barr what was going 
to happen there, but when Barr arrived  

989
01:32:10,640 --> 01:32:12,320
he found a room waiting for him.  

990
01:32:13,680 --> 01:32:18,960
A note at the front desk of the hotel said he 
would receive a phone call in the early morning.

991
01:32:20,240 --> 01:32:25,840
He called Fletcher Coal at home 
at ten and told him the news.

992
01:32:26,440 --> 01:32:27,440
***

993
01:32:27,440 --> 01:32:35,520
She stepped on the note when she opened her door. 
It said: Darby, I'm in the garden. It's urgent.  

994
01:32:36,240 --> 01:32:43,120
Gray. She locked the door, went downstairs, 
through the restaurant and out into the garden.  

995
01:32:43,920 --> 01:32:48,160
She found him sitting at a small 
table, half hidden behind a wall.

996
01:32:49,520 --> 01:32:57,120
'Why are you here?' she demanded in a whisper. He 
told her what had happened, and what he'd done for  

997
01:32:57,120 --> 01:33:03,120
the rest of the day. He had spent it riding 
round the city in a dozen different taxis,  

998
01:33:03,120 --> 01:33:10,080
waiting for dark. Then he came to the Tabard. 
He was certain that no one had followed him.

999
01:33:11,520 --> 01:33:17,040
She listened. She watched the restaurant and the 
entrance to the garden, and heard every word.

1000
01:33:18,960 --> 01:33:23,040
'I have no idea how anyone 
could find my room,' he said.

1001
01:33:23,840 --> 01:33:25,600
'Did you tell anyone your room number?'  

1002
01:33:26,720 --> 01:33:32,560
He thought for a second. 'Only Smith Keen, 
but he didn't have time to tell anyone else.'

1003
01:33:33,920 --> 01:33:36,320
'Where were you when you told him?'

1004
01:33:36,320 --> 01:33:36,960
'In his car.'

1005
01:33:38,320 --> 01:33:43,040
She shook her head slowly. 'I told 
you not to tell anyone, didn't I?  

1006
01:33:44,000 --> 01:33:52,080
You think this is all a game. It's not, Gray, it's 
real. This isn't just a great newspaper story,  

1007
01:33:52,080 --> 01:33:55,760
which is going to make Gray 
Grantham famous and win him prizes.  

1008
01:33:56,800 --> 01:34:04,720
I've seen people die. God knows how many times 
I've been close to death myself. These people  

1009
01:34:04,720 --> 01:34:10,800
are dangerous, and they're professionals. 
They know about you and the Washington Post.  

1010
01:34:11,520 --> 01:34:15,920
They've probably been listening to you since 
you wrote the first story about this matter.  

1011
01:34:16,800 --> 01:34:22,960
They'll have microphones hidden in your 
apartment, your car and your office. It  

1012
01:34:22,960 --> 01:34:28,640
looks as though they've got microphones in Keen's 
car as well. Do you understand what I'm saying?  

1013
01:34:29,840 --> 01:34:34,080
Last night at dinner we tried to 
pretend we were two normal people  

1014
01:34:34,080 --> 01:34:39,840
getting to know each other. But 
that wasn't real: this is real.'

1015
01:34:41,600 --> 01:34:46,640
She was right, of course. He felt like a 
schoolchild in front of an angry teacher.

1016
01:34:48,080 --> 01:34:54,400
'You can stay here tonight,' she said, 'and 
tomorrow I'll find you another small hotel.'

1017
01:34:55,480 --> 01:34:56,480
***

1018
01:34:56,480 --> 01:35:00,160
After breakfast the next 
morning she got on the phone.  

1019
01:35:00,160 --> 01:35:04,720
She rang the Georgetown law school and 
pretended to be from White and Blazevich.  

1020
01:35:06,480 --> 01:35:11,040
She said that their computers were not 
working, and that for the sake of her records  

1021
01:35:11,040 --> 01:35:15,200
she needed to know which students had 
worked for White and Blazevich last summer.  

1022
01:35:16,880 --> 01:35:20,400
She waited, with her hand over 
the mouthpiece of the phone,  

1023
01:35:20,960 --> 01:35:26,080
and looked at Gray. The secretary from 
the law school came back on the phone.  

1024
01:35:27,680 --> 01:35:35,040
'Seven of them,' Darby said. 'Thank you.' 
She wrote down their names. 'And do you have  

1025
01:35:35,040 --> 01:35:41,840
their addresses, please? We need them for our 
records.' She wrote down this information too.

1026
01:35:42,720 --> 01:35:46,160
'That was brilliant,' Gray 
said when she had finished.  

1027
01:35:47,440 --> 01:35:52,800
'Now all we need to do is find as many of 
these students as we can, show them your  

1028
01:35:52,800 --> 01:35:58,320
photograph of Garcia, and hope that one of them 
recognizes him and can tell us his real name.'

1029
01:35:59,920 --> 01:36:03,680
'Why couldn't we just wait outside 
the firm's building until he came out,  

1030
01:36:03,680 --> 01:36:08,160
and then follow him? That's what Croft 
was doing at Brim, Stearns and Kidlow.'

1031
01:36:09,200 --> 01:36:14,800
'Too risky. It seems likely that White and 
Blazevich were involved in some way in the  

1032
01:36:14,800 --> 01:36:21,520
killings. There are people who know my face, 
and we know they're looking for you too. What  

1033
01:36:21,520 --> 01:36:26,400
if they're guarding White and Blazevich? 
They would see us, and then we'd be dead.'

1034
01:36:28,400 --> 01:36:35,680
They hired a car and began to try to find the 
seven students. Gray found two of them at home and  

1035
01:36:35,680 --> 01:36:41,600
Darby spoke to another as he was leaving a class 
at the school; none of them recognized Garcia.  

1036
01:36:42,800 --> 01:36:50,480
They met at 10:45 and compared notes. At eleven, 
students were leaving their classes and she found  

1037
01:36:50,480 --> 01:36:57,200
another of the seven students, but he too knew 
nothing. A fifth was working in the library;  

1038
01:36:58,240 --> 01:37:03,120
she didn't like answering Darby's questions, 
but she admitted that she didn't know Garcia.

1039
01:37:04,560 --> 01:37:12,960
Only two left - Edward Linney and Judith Wilson. 
Wilson was expected back at her apartment at one  

1040
01:37:12,960 --> 01:37:20,160
o'clock, so Gray spent the rest of the morning 
trying to find Linney, but he was not at home  

1041
01:37:20,160 --> 01:37:25,840
and no one at the school seemed to know where 
he was. They hadn't seen him for several weeks.

1042
01:37:27,600 --> 01:37:33,840
They drove together to Judith Wilson's apartment. 
She wasn't there at one, so they waited.  

1043
01:37:35,040 --> 01:37:41,120
She arrived an hour later. Gray jumped 
out of the car, ran up to her and caught  

1044
01:37:41,120 --> 01:37:47,840
her at her front door. He showed her the 
photograph, and Darby saw her shake her head.

1045
01:37:48,960 --> 01:37:54,400
'Linney had better be good,' he said as he 
got back into the car. 'But where is he?'

1046
01:37:55,600 --> 01:38:01,840
'I hope we find him today,' she said, 'because 
tomorrow I leave the country if we don't.'

1047
01:38:03,680 --> 01:38:08,480
Back at the law school, one of his fellow 
students at last told them where he was:  

1048
01:38:09,680 --> 01:38:16,400
in a private hospital. He was well on the way 
to becoming an alcoholic, and his parents had  

1049
01:38:16,400 --> 01:38:22,880
ordered him to spend some time there. The nurse 
at the front desk of the hospital told Gray that  

1050
01:38:22,880 --> 01:38:30,240
Mr Linney was in Room 22, but refused to let 
him see him. Gray asked to see the manager,  

1051
01:38:30,800 --> 01:38:36,320
and while the nurse was fetching him 
Gray whispered to Darby, 'Room 22.'

1052
01:38:38,000 --> 01:38:41,040
She left the waiting-room and 
boldly walked to his room.  

1053
01:38:41,760 --> 01:38:46,640
She knocked and went in. The young 
man looked surprised to see her.

1054
01:38:47,840 --> 01:38:54,240
'I'm Sara Jacobs,' she said. 'I work for the 
Washington Post. May I ask you a question?'

1055
01:38:55,600 --> 01:38:57,840
'Yes, but how did you get in?'

1056
01:38:58,880 --> 01:39:03,920
'I just walked in. You worked at White 
and Blazevich last summer, didn't you?  

1057
01:39:04,880 --> 01:39:09,120
Do you recognize this man?' 
She showed him the photograph.

1058
01:39:10,000 --> 01:39:17,440
'Yes, he's . . . what's his name? I can't 
remember. He works in the oil and gas department.'

1059
01:39:18,640 --> 01:39:19,760
Darby held her breath.

1060
01:39:20,720 --> 01:39:27,440
Linney closed his eyes and thought. 'Morgan. 
Yes, that's it. His surname is Morgan,  

1061
01:39:28,000 --> 01:39:31,920
but I can't remember his first 
name. What's this all about?'

1062
01:39:33,040 --> 01:39:36,800
'I'll tell you later,' Darby said, and left.

1063
01:39:38,480 --> 01:39:40,720
Gray was waiting for her back in the car.  

1064
01:39:41,680 --> 01:39:46,400
She didn't say anything but immediately looked 
at the notes she had taken in the law library.  

1065
01:39:47,600 --> 01:39:55,200
There he was. 'Garcia is Curtis D. 
Morgan,' she said. 'Let's go.'
 
 
 
 
 

1066
01:39:59,520 --> 01:40:00,480
CHAPTER FIFTEEN

1067
01:40:01,360 --> 01:40:02,400
Two Appointments
 

1068
01:40:04,080 --> 01:40:11,040
After five hours at sea in the small, fast boat, 
every bone in Matthew Barr's body was aching,  

1069
01:40:11,040 --> 01:40:16,720
and he was wet and cold. His only 
companion had been a man called Larry,  

1070
01:40:16,720 --> 01:40:19,760
who was extremely tall and looked very strong.  

1071
01:40:21,520 --> 01:40:26,080
Larry had met him in Fort Lauderdale and 
had not said a word to him since then.

1072
01:40:27,760 --> 01:40:34,320
They landed in a country Barr believed was the 
Bahamas. A car took them to a small airfield,  

1073
01:40:34,320 --> 01:40:38,960
where a Lear jet was waiting. The 
flight took about forty-five minutes.  

1074
01:40:40,240 --> 01:40:45,520
Another car took them to a large house. 
Barr had no idea where they were.

1075
01:40:47,200 --> 01:40:49,840
Barr was met by a man who called himself Emil,  

1076
01:40:50,560 --> 01:40:53,520
who led him round the outside 
of the house to a sunroom.

1077
01:40:55,360 --> 01:40:59,840
'I'm afraid you must take off your 
shoes,' Emil said with a polite smile,  

1078
01:41:00,480 --> 01:41:03,840
'and be careful not to step on the towels.'

1079
01:41:04,480 --> 01:41:09,680
Inside, Barr saw that towels were lying on 
the floor of the sun- room, making paths  

1080
01:41:09,680 --> 01:41:16,320
around the room. A door on the other side of 
the room opened, and Victor Mattiece came in.

1081
01:41:17,600 --> 01:41:25,040
Barr stared. Mattiece was an extraordinary 
sight. He was extremely thin, and had  

1082
01:41:25,040 --> 01:41:30,800
long grey hair and a beard. He wore 
only a pair of black sports shorts.  

1083
01:41:31,760 --> 01:41:37,280
His toenails were yellow and very 
long. He looked completely crazy.

1084
01:41:39,760 --> 01:41:47,040
'Sit over there,' he said, pointing at 
a chair. 'Don't step on the towels.'

1085
01:41:48,640 --> 01:41:56,880
When Barr was seated, Mattiece asked, 'What 
do you want?' He was staring out of a window.

1086
01:41:58,240 --> 01:42:01,280
'The President sent me,' Barr began.

1087
01:42:02,480 --> 01:42:06,320
'He did not. Fletcher Coal sent you.'

1088
01:42:07,920 --> 01:42:13,840
'All right. We need to know whether the 
Pelican Brief is true. Have you read it?'

1089
01:42:14,960 --> 01:42:15,520
'Have you?'

1090
01:42:16,720 --> 01:42:17,040
'Yes.'

1091
01:42:18,480 --> 01:42:20,800
'Does Mr Coal believe it to be true?'

1092
01:42:22,320 --> 01:42:29,200
'I don't know. He's very worried. That's 
why I'm here, Mr Mattiece. We have to know.'

1093
01:42:30,640 --> 01:42:32,000
'What if it is true?'

1094
01:42:33,440 --> 01:42:34,880
'Then we have problems.'

1095
01:42:36,320 --> 01:42:39,760
Mattiece turned away from the 
window, looked at Barr and said,  

1096
01:42:41,360 --> 01:42:49,360
'Do you know what I think? I think Coal is the 
problem. He let too many people see the brief.'

1097
01:42:51,360 --> 01:42:56,960
Barr could not believe what he was hearing. 
The man who had ordered so many deaths was  

1098
01:42:56,960 --> 01:43:05,280
blaming someone else for the situation. 'Is it 
true, Mr Mattiece? That's all I want to know.'

1099
01:43:07,200 --> 01:43:10,480
Behind Barr, a door opened without a sound.  

1100
01:43:11,760 --> 01:43:16,880
Larry, in his socks and avoiding the 
towels, stepped silently into the room.

1101
01:43:18,480 --> 01:43:24,480
Mattiece walked over to the door and 
said softly, 'Of course it's true.'  

1102
01:43:26,320 --> 01:43:28,800
He left the sun-room and went into the garden.

1103
01:43:30,480 --> 01:43:32,400
Now what? Barr thought.

1104
01:43:33,840 --> 01:43:40,000
Larry put the rope round Barr's neck, and Barr did 
not hear or feel anything until it was too late.  

1105
01:43:41,440 --> 01:43:46,560
Mattiece did not want blood on the 
floor, so Larry simply broke his neck.

1106
01:43:47,960 --> 01:43:48,960
***

1107
01:43:48,960 --> 01:43:53,440
They reached the building where White and 
Blazevich's offices were before five o'clock.  

1108
01:43:54,560 --> 01:43:58,320
She was wearing a dress, and 
Gray said she looked just right.  

1109
01:44:00,000 --> 01:44:02,560
She could tell that he liked the way she looked,  

1110
01:44:02,560 --> 01:44:08,560
and she found to her surprise that it didn't 
make her angry, just a little sad about Thomas.

1111
01:44:10,400 --> 01:44:14,880
She walked up to the secretary at 
the desk, who said, 'Can I help you?'

1112
01:44:16,480 --> 01:44:23,760
'Yes, I have an appointment at five o'clock 
with Curtis Morgan. My name is Dorothy Blythe.'

1113
01:44:24,960 --> 01:44:28,000
The secretary's mouth fell 
open and she said nothing.

1114
01:44:29,200 --> 01:44:32,560
Darby's heart stopped. 'Is something the matter?'

1115
01:44:33,680 --> 01:44:39,680
'Can you wait a moment?' the secretary said. 
She got up and disappeared into another room.

1116
01:44:40,880 --> 01:44:48,000
Run, Darby's mind was telling her, run! 
There's something wrong here. But before  

1117
01:44:48,000 --> 01:44:51,520
she had time to do anything, the 
secretary returned with a man.

1118
01:44:53,120 --> 01:44:59,600
'Good afternoon,' he said. 'I'm Jarreld 
Schwabe, one of the partners of the firm.  

1119
01:45:00,560 --> 01:45:03,600
You say you have an appointment 
with Curtis Morgan?'

1120
01:45:04,720 --> 01:45:06,880
'Yes. Is there a problem?'

1121
01:45:08,000 --> 01:45:10,000
'There's nothing in his appointment book.'

1122
01:45:10,960 --> 01:45:12,800
'Well, that's your fault, not mine.'

1123
01:45:13,920 --> 01:45:15,840
'And what was the meeting about?'

1124
01:45:16,720 --> 01:45:23,360
She felt weak. 'I don't see why I have to 
tell you that. Why can't I see Mr Morgan?'

1125
01:45:24,800 --> 01:45:25,840
'Because he's dead.'

1126
01:45:27,200 --> 01:45:29,680
She was in shock. 'Dead?'

1127
01:45:31,440 --> 01:45:35,760
'Yes,' Schwabe said. 'He was mugged in the street.  

1128
01:45:37,040 --> 01:45:40,880
I'm sorry. I can see this 
has been a shock for you.'

1129
01:45:42,320 --> 01:45:47,200
She decided to act really upset. She 
didn't want them to ask any more questions;  

1130
01:45:48,000 --> 01:45:50,960
she wanted them to think that 
she was just a weak young woman.  

1131
01:45:52,400 --> 01:45:58,960
'I'm sorry,' she said, 'I think I'd better 
go. I'll phone again for another appointment.'

1132
01:46:00,560 --> 01:46:02,400
Schwabe led her to the lift himself.

1133
01:46:05,440 --> 01:46:11,120
Edwin Sneller knew that he and his men had been 
wasting their time in New York; the place was  

1134
01:46:11,120 --> 01:46:18,960
just too big. Then at last she moved some money 
from her bank in New Orleans to Grantham's bank  

1135
01:46:18,960 --> 01:46:25,840
in Washington. Sneller's client owned the bank, 
so he received any information he asked for.  

1136
01:46:26,720 --> 01:46:31,600
That meant that she was in Washington, and that 
she and the reporter were working together.  

1137
01:46:32,880 --> 01:46:40,720
He had two men with him, and he had asked for 
more. They had to do the job quickly. But he  

1138
01:46:40,720 --> 01:46:47,680
felt less confident without Khamel. The girl had 
escaped so far, and she could be hiding anywhere.  

1139
01:46:48,880 --> 01:46:54,400
He would start with the Washington Post building: 
Grantham had to come back there some time.

1140
01:46:56,040 --> 01:46:57,040
***

1141
01:46:57,040 --> 01:47:02,480
Gray found Curtis D. Morgan's address in the 
suburbs, and they drove out together to the house.  

1142
01:47:03,920 --> 01:47:07,840
Mrs Morgan's father, however, 
refused to let them in to see her.  

1143
01:47:08,880 --> 01:47:12,800
Gray left his business card, so that 
she could call him if she wanted to.  

1144
01:47:14,080 --> 01:47:18,960
He told her father that Morgan had spoken 
to him three times just before he died.

1145
01:47:20,720 --> 01:47:25,120
'Is that the end of Garcia?' 
Darby asked as they drove away.

1146
01:47:26,320 --> 01:47:30,880
'We'll see tomorrow,' he said. 
'How do you feel at the moment?  

1147
01:47:31,600 --> 01:47:37,680
Do you feel safe? I'll be glad to sleep in your 
room tonight, just like I did in New York.'

1148
01:47:39,200 --> 01:47:44,000
'But I don't have a sofa here,' 
she said. 'Where would you sleep?'  

1149
01:47:45,600 --> 01:47:51,040
She was smiling and this was a good 
sign. But then she remembered Callahan.  

1150
01:47:52,880 --> 01:47:58,880
'I'm not ready, Gray. I'm sorry.' She rested 
her head on his shoulder while he drove the car.  

1151
01:48:00,160 --> 01:48:03,840
'I'm still frightened to death,' she said.
 
 
 
 
 

1152
01:48:07,200 --> 01:48:08,160
CHAPTER SIXTEEN

1153
01:48:09,120 --> 01:48:10,240
Morgan's Story
 

1154
01:48:12,240 --> 01:48:15,440
Beverly Morgan called Gray at 
four o'clock the next morning.  

1155
01:48:17,280 --> 01:48:20,560
'My father would be angry with 
me if he knew I was calling,'  

1156
01:48:21,120 --> 01:48:27,360
she said. 'The reporters were horrible to us after 
Curtis was killed. But I need to talk to someone.'

1157
01:48:28,720 --> 01:48:34,240
She asked him how he knew her husband, and Gray 
explained about his phone calls, and the murders  

1158
01:48:34,240 --> 01:48:40,960
of Rosenberg and Jensen. He spoke to her patiently 
for a long time, until he won her confidence.

1159
01:48:42,320 --> 01:48:44,640
'What do you think he knew?' she asked.

1160
01:48:45,600 --> 01:48:50,800
'I have no idea. If he had written 
something down on paper, where would it be?'

1161
01:48:51,920 --> 01:48:57,040
'In our lock-box in the bank. But 
that's where all his legal papers were,  

1162
01:48:57,040 --> 01:49:02,720
so I've already looked in there. I did find 
another key in his desk, though, last Saturday.'

1163
01:49:03,680 --> 01:49:07,440
Gray held his breath. 'A key to another lock-box?'

1164
01:49:08,640 --> 01:49:14,960
'Yes, a box at First Columbia Bank. That's 
odd, because we've never used that bank.  

1165
01:49:16,160 --> 01:49:19,680
I wasn't in a hurry to go to 
the bank and look in the box,  

1166
01:49:19,680 --> 01:49:25,680
because I already had all his legal papers. Maybe 
it was even something I wouldn't want to see.'

1167
01:49:27,200 --> 01:49:30,880
'Would you like me to look in 
the box for you?' Gray asked.

1168
01:49:31,760 --> 01:49:34,400
'I hoped you would say that. Yes, please.'

1169
01:49:35,280 --> 01:49:36,880
'I'll come round and get the key now'

1170
01:49:37,960 --> 01:49:38,960
***

1171
01:49:38,960 --> 01:49:44,320
He and Darby drove to the bank the 
next morning. Mrs Morgan had given  

1172
01:49:44,320 --> 01:49:49,680
Gray written permission to open the lock-box, 
so the clerk let them into the strong-room.  

1173
01:49:51,040 --> 01:49:55,840
It didn't take them long to empty the 
box: all it held was a thin envelope.

1174
01:49:57,680 --> 01:50:00,320
Darby opened the envelope when 
they were back in the car.  

1175
01:50:01,760 --> 01:50:09,440
Inside was a document written by Morgan and 
properly signed by a legal witness. The document  

1176
01:50:09,440 --> 01:50:18,480
started: 'Since you are reading this, I am 
probably dead.' It was a powerful first sentence.

1177
01:50:20,240 --> 01:50:24,800
In the document Morgan described 
who he was and where he worked.  

1178
01:50:26,000 --> 01:50:31,520
He said that he often worked for one of the 
firm's clients who was called Victor Mattiece.  

1179
01:50:32,880 --> 01:50:41,200
The partner in charge of Mr Mattiece was F. Sims 
Wakefield. Morgan explained the Louisiana case  

1180
01:50:41,200 --> 01:50:47,280
and how important it was to Mr Mattiece. It 
was important to White and Blazevich too,  

1181
01:50:48,000 --> 01:50:51,840
since Mattiece had promised them a 
share of the profits from the oil.

1182
01:50:53,600 --> 01:51:01,600
On or about 28 September, the document continued, 
Morgan had been in Wakefield's office collecting  

1183
01:51:01,600 --> 01:51:09,760
some files. When he returned to his own office, he 
found that by mistake he had picked up a note from  

1184
01:51:09,760 --> 01:51:17,360
Wakefield's desk together with the files. A copy 
of the note was joined on to Morgan's document.  

1185
01:51:18,880 --> 01:51:28,880
The note was dated 28 September and was from 
Marty Velmano, another partner. It read: Sims:  

1186
01:51:30,320 --> 01:51:35,440
Tell our client that the Court will be 
easier on him if Rosenberg is retired.  

1187
01:51:36,640 --> 01:51:44,000
The second retirement is a bit unusual 
- it is Jensen (who, as you know,  

1188
01:51:44,640 --> 01:51:54,240
has those other problems). The note amazed and 
frightened Morgan. Realizing its importance,  

1189
01:51:54,240 --> 01:51:58,960
he made a copy of it and returned the 
original to the bottom of the pile of files.

1190
01:52:00,400 --> 01:52:08,400
Ten minutes later Wakefield came into his office, 
looking pale and worried. They found the note  

1191
01:52:08,400 --> 01:52:12,560
under the files and Wakefield 
asked Morgan if he had read it;  

1192
01:52:13,600 --> 01:52:20,640
Morgan said no. Wakefield looked at 
him very closely, but seemed satisfied.

1193
01:52:22,160 --> 01:52:25,760
That night he left the 
papers on his desk very tidy.  

1194
01:52:26,880 --> 01:52:33,280
The next morning he could see that someone 
had searched his desk. He began to see  

1195
01:52:33,280 --> 01:52:40,480
Velmano in Wakefield's office more than usual. 
Wakefield stopped him working for Mattiece.

1196
01:52:42,000 --> 01:52:49,280
Then Rosenberg and Jensen were killed. He was 
sure that Mattiece had ordered the killings.  

1197
01:52:50,720 --> 01:52:57,040
He thought that people were following him. 
He had decided to hide his copy of the note  

1198
01:52:57,040 --> 01:53:03,760
together with this document in a bank, in 
case he was killed. He was very frightened.

1199
01:53:05,440 --> 01:53:07,360
That was the end of the document.

1200
01:53:08,760 --> 01:53:09,760
***

1201
01:53:09,760 --> 01:53:16,320
The thin-faced man watched the car come fast 
round the corner and park illegally outside the  

1202
01:53:16,320 --> 01:53:22,720
Post building. The man and the woman jumped out 
of the car and ran past him into the building.

1203
01:53:24,000 --> 01:53:28,800
He had a gun inside his jacket, 
but it all happened too fast.

1204
01:53:29,400 --> 01:53:30,400
***

1205
01:53:30,400 --> 01:53:34,320
Smith Keen and the Post's lawyer, Vincent Litsky,  

1206
01:53:35,040 --> 01:53:42,240
read through Morgan's document. When they 
had finished, Gray said, 'Well, gentlemen,  

1207
01:53:42,960 --> 01:53:47,200
there's your independent witness. 
Can we print Darby's story now?'

1208
01:53:48,800 --> 01:53:50,880
Keen and Litsky looked at each other.  

1209
01:53:52,160 --> 01:53:55,840
Keen left the office for a few minutes 
to speak to the newspaper's owner.  

1210
01:53:57,120 --> 01:54:04,960
When he came back he said, 'OK, Gray. We do the 
story. How long will it take you to write it?'

1211
01:54:06,240 --> 01:54:09,040
'I already know the shape of it,' Gray replied.  

1212
01:54:09,680 --> 01:54:14,320
'I only have to write the details. 
It should take me about two hours.'

1213
01:54:15,440 --> 01:54:20,720
'It's eleven o'clock now,' Keen 
said. 'Try to finish it by three.  

1214
01:54:21,680 --> 01:54:24,160
Litsky needs time to read it before we print.'

1215
01:54:26,000 --> 01:54:32,880
With Darby's help, he finished the story on time. 
Keen and Litsky read it and made some changes.  

1216
01:54:34,320 --> 01:54:36,560
Darby was watching something out of the window.

1217
01:54:38,400 --> 01:54:41,680
'When I've rewritten the story,' Gray said,  

1218
01:54:41,680 --> 01:54:46,000
when Keen and Litsky had finished, 
'I have to make some phone calls.'

1219
01:54:47,200 --> 01:54:50,560
'We'll be back at half past three,' Keen said.

1220
01:54:52,480 --> 01:54:57,920
'They're outside,' Darby said softly, 
when Keen and Litsky had left the room.

1221
01:54:58,640 --> 01:54:59,200
'Who are?'

1222
01:55:00,400 --> 01:55:06,640
'I was watching a man standing on the corner. 
He looks innocent enough; he's just standing  

1223
01:55:06,640 --> 01:55:13,280
there drinking coffee from a cup. But he's been 
there a long time - I saw him earlier as well.  

1224
01:55:14,320 --> 01:55:20,640
And just now, when you were talking, I saw the 
short man who chased me last week come up to  

1225
01:55:20,640 --> 01:55:26,080
the coffee-drinker. They talked for a minute 
and then the short man disappeared again.  

1226
01:55:27,440 --> 01:55:31,840
They're just waiting for us 
to leave the building.'
 
 
 
 
 

1227
01:55:33,600 --> 01:55:34,560
CHAPTER SEVENTEEN

1228
01:55:35,600 --> 01:55:36,960
Time to Trust Someone
 

1229
01:55:38,880 --> 01:55:42,240
The first phone call was to a 
friend of Grantham at the FBI.

1230
01:55:43,440 --> 01:55:47,440
'Phil, this is Gray Grantham. 
I've got the recorder on.'

1231
01:55:48,880 --> 01:55:51,120
'That sounds serious. Go on.'

1232
01:55:52,160 --> 01:55:58,480
'We're going to print a story tomorrow about the 
Rosenberg and Jensen killings. We're going to name  

1233
01:55:58,480 --> 01:56:04,000
Victor Mattiece as the man behind the killings, 
and also two of his lawyers here in Washington.  

1234
01:56:05,200 --> 01:56:10,560
We'll connect this story with the killing 
of Verheek in New Orleans. We believe the  

1235
01:56:10,560 --> 01:56:16,320
FBI knew about Mattiece early on but refused to 
investigate at the request of the White House.  

1236
01:56:17,440 --> 01:56:24,560
We want to give you the chance to comment.' 
There was silence. 'Phil, are you there?'

1237
01:56:26,160 --> 01:56:28,160
'Yes, I think so.'

1238
01:56:29,200 --> 01:56:29,920
'Any comment?'

1239
01:56:31,360 --> 01:56:34,880
'I'm sure we will have a comment, 
but I'll have to call you back.'

1240
01:56:35,760 --> 01:56:37,840
'OK. I'll look forward to it.'

1241
01:56:39,360 --> 01:56:43,680
In fact it was Voyles himself who 
called back, about ten minutes later.  

1242
01:56:44,320 --> 01:56:46,000
He demanded to speak to Smith Keen.

1243
01:56:47,280 --> 01:56:52,000
'What are you doing, Smith?' he said. 
'We're still investigating Mattiece.  

1244
01:56:52,000 --> 01:56:56,240
It's too early to be sure. What have you got?'

1245
01:56:56,240 --> 01:56:59,920
'Does the name Darby Shaw mean 
anything to you?' Keen asked.

1246
01:57:00,720 --> 01:57:01,040
'Yes.'

1247
01:57:02,160 --> 01:57:06,720
'We have the Pelican Brief, Denton, and 
I'm sitting here looking at Darby Shaw.'

1248
01:57:07,920 --> 01:57:10,160
'I was afraid she was dead.'

1249
01:57:10,160 --> 01:57:15,440
'No, she's not. And she and Gray Grantham have 
an independent witness to support the brief.  

1250
01:57:16,160 --> 01:57:17,520
It's a big story, Denton.'

1251
01:57:18,880 --> 01:57:22,480
'We need to meet. I'll come 
round in twenty minutes.'

1252
01:57:23,440 --> 01:57:23,840
'OK.'

1253
01:57:25,760 --> 01:57:30,880
Keen put the phone down and smiled. 
He was amused at the idea of the great  

1254
01:57:30,880 --> 01:57:34,560
F. Denton Voyles coming round 
to his office for a meeting.

1255
01:57:36,240 --> 01:57:40,400
The next phone call Gray made was 
to Fletcher Coal in the White House.  

1256
01:57:41,600 --> 01:57:46,320
Coal agreed that Mattiece had given large amounts 
of money towards the President's election,  

1257
01:57:46,960 --> 01:57:50,240
but denied that Mattiece and the 
President were close friends.  

1258
01:57:51,520 --> 01:57:54,320
He had to admit that he was 
familiar with the Pelican Brief.  

1259
01:57:55,760 --> 01:57:59,840
When Gray asked why there had not been 
an immediate investigation of Mattiece,  

1260
01:58:00,480 --> 01:58:05,840
Coal angrily denied that the White House had 
tried to slow down such an investigation.

1261
01:58:07,040 --> 01:58:14,960
Then Voyles arrived with K. O. Lewis. Keen took 
him into his own office and gave him a copy of the  

1262
01:58:14,960 --> 01:58:21,920
story to read while Gray made the third phone 
call. He rang White and Blazevich and was put  

1263
01:58:21,920 --> 01:58:28,320
through to Marty Velmano. For the third time he 
explained that he was recording the conversation.

1264
01:58:29,520 --> 01:58:34,640
'Mr Velmano,' Gray said, 'we're 
printing a story in the morning which  

1265
01:58:34,640 --> 01:58:40,000
names your client Victor Mattiece as the man 
behind thekillings of Rosenberg and Jensen.'

1266
01:58:41,200 --> 01:58:45,520
'Good!' said Velmano. 'We'll take you to court.  

1267
01:58:46,480 --> 01:58:50,960
By the time we're finished, Mr 
Mattiece will own the Washington Post.'

1268
01:58:52,400 --> 01:58:57,920
'Mr Velmano, we have a copy of the 
Pelican Brief. Have you heard of it?'

1269
01:58:59,280 --> 01:58:59,840
Silence.

1270
01:59:00,800 --> 01:59:06,880
'We also have a copy of a note you 
sent to Sims Wakefield on 28 September.  

1271
01:59:08,000 --> 01:59:11,600
In the note you suggested 
that your client's position  

1272
01:59:11,600 --> 01:59:15,840
would be a lot better without Rosenberg 
and Jensen on the Supreme Court.'

1273
01:59:17,360 --> 01:59:17,920
Silence.

1274
01:59:19,120 --> 01:59:21,600
'Mr Velmano, are you there?'

1275
01:59:23,040 --> 01:59:23,360
'Yes.'

1276
01:59:25,040 --> 01:59:29,840
'We wanted to give you the chance to 
comment. Do you have any comment?'

1277
01:59:31,040 --> 01:59:34,640
'You're going to destroy me,' Velmano said.

1278
01:59:36,280 --> 01:59:37,280
***

1279
01:59:37,280 --> 01:59:43,840
Voyles and Lewis entered the room with Smith 
Keen. Keen introduced them to Darby and Gray.  

1280
01:59:44,400 --> 01:59:49,760
Voyles smiled at Darby and said, 'So 
you're the one who started all this.'

1281
01:59:50,880 --> 01:59:54,080
'No, sir,' she said, 'I think it was Mattiece.'

1282
01:59:55,520 --> 02:00:02,560
They sat around a table. Voyles had a piece of 
paper. He said, 'I'm going to read you something.  

1283
02:00:03,440 --> 02:00:06,560
This is official, and you 
can use it in your paper.  

1284
02:00:07,680 --> 02:00:13,760
Anything else Lewis or I say is unofficial, 
and you can't use it. Is that clear?'

1285
02:00:15,200 --> 02:00:16,560
Keen and Grantham said yes.

1286
02:00:17,680 --> 02:00:25,760
'All right,' Voyles said. 'We received a copy of 
the Pelican Brief two weeks ago and showed it to  

1287
02:00:25,760 --> 02:00:32,720
the White House on the same day. It was personally 
delivered by K. O. Lewis to Fletcher Coal.  

1288
02:00:33,920 --> 02:00:39,840
Eric East was also present at the meeting. 
We thought it was worth investigation,  

1289
02:00:40,720 --> 02:00:46,160
but nothing happened for six days, until 
Gavin Verheek was murdered in New Orleans.  

1290
02:00:47,680 --> 02:00:53,840
The FBI began a full investigation into Victor 
Mattiece, involving over four hundred men.  

1291
02:00:55,600 --> 02:01:00,560
We believe Victor Mattiece to be the 
main suspect in the murders of Rosenberg,  

1292
02:01:00,560 --> 02:01:05,440
Jensen, Thomas Callahan and Verheek, 
and we are trying to find him.'

1293
02:01:07,280 --> 02:01:12,160
'Did the White House interfere with your 
investigation of Mattiece?' Grantham asked.

1294
02:01:13,360 --> 02:01:19,120
'This is now unofficial,' Voyles 
said. 'You can't use it. OK?'

1295
02:01:20,320 --> 02:01:21,840
'OK.'

1296
02:01:22,400 --> 02:01:26,560
'Yes, the President asked me 
not to investigate Mattiece.  

1297
02:01:27,440 --> 02:01:32,800
He said it could be embarrassing to the 
Government. I recorded the conversation.'

1298
02:01:34,240 --> 02:01:38,400
They could hardly believe what they 
were hearing. He recorded the President!

1299
02:01:39,840 --> 02:01:46,800
'I will not allow anyone to hear that recording,' 
Voyles continued, 'unless the President denies  

1300
02:01:46,800 --> 02:01:53,440
what I have just told you. Anyway, will 
you use the official story I've given you?  

1301
02:01:54,160 --> 02:01:57,840
Will you put Coal's name there on the 
front page along with everyone else?'

1302
02:02:00,400 --> 02:02:03,840
'Yes, I think he belongs there,' Keen said.

1303
02:02:04,880 --> 02:02:11,200
'Good,' said Voyles. 'Can you give me some 
early copies of the newspaper tomorrow morning?  

1304
02:02:12,320 --> 02:02:15,520
I want to take them round to 
him myself and watch his face.'

1305
02:02:17,040 --> 02:02:21,920
'He'll take the blame,' Keen said. 
'It will be the end of his career,  

1306
02:02:22,560 --> 02:02:24,640
but he'll make the President look innocent.'

1307
02:02:26,160 --> 02:02:29,680
'Yes, I think you're right,' said Voyles.  

1308
02:02:30,720 --> 02:02:35,920
'Now, I'd like to speak to Miss Shaw alone, 
please, if that's all right with her.'

1309
02:02:37,120 --> 02:02:40,320
'OK,' she said, 'but Grantham stays.'

1310
02:02:41,440 --> 02:02:41,920
'All right.'

1311
02:02:43,520 --> 02:02:49,120
When everyone else had left the room, Voyles 
asked, 'What are you going to do next?'

1312
02:02:50,720 --> 02:02:54,160
'First tell me who killed 
Gavin Verheek,' she said.

1313
02:02:55,680 --> 02:02:59,520
'It was Khamel. And Khamel was the one who  

1314
02:02:59,520 --> 02:03:02,320
was shot in the head as you were 
holding his hand by the river.'

1315
02:03:03,440 --> 02:03:04,320
'Who killed him?'

1316
02:03:05,760 --> 02:03:12,320
'We think it was someone from the CIA. We know the 
CIA were investigating Mattiece in a small way.  

1317
02:03:13,440 --> 02:03:18,400
In his oil business Mattiece had connections 
with some unfriendly Arab countries,  

1318
02:03:18,960 --> 02:03:24,320
so the CIA were already keeping an 
eye on him. When they saw a copy of  

1319
02:03:24,320 --> 02:03:28,720
the Pelican Brief they sent a few men 
down to New Orleans to look after you.'

1320
02:03:30,080 --> 02:03:36,960
Darby got up and went to the window. It was dark 
outside now. 'They didn't do a very good job,  

1321
02:03:36,960 --> 02:03:42,720
then,' she said. 'There are men out there now 
who have been following me for a week or more.  

1322
02:03:43,840 --> 02:03:49,840
One of them chased me in New Orleans, so 
I don't think he's CIA. Mattiece is so  

1323
02:03:49,840 --> 02:03:56,320
crazy that he'll go on trying to kill me even 
after he goes to prison - if you catch him.'

1324
02:03:56,320 --> 02:04:00,960
'We can help,' Voyles said. 'We 
can get you out of the country.'

1325
02:04:02,400 --> 02:04:10,240
It was time to trust someone. She took 
a deep breath. 'All right,' she said.

1326
02:04:10,240 --> 02:04:13,280
'I'll go and make the arrangements,' Voyles said.

1327
02:04:14,480 --> 02:04:20,080
Alone in the room, Darby walked into Gray's 
arms. 'It's going to be all right now,'  

1328
02:04:20,720 --> 02:04:24,240
he said, holding her. 'It's over. You're safe.'

1329
02:04:25,760 --> 02:04:30,400
'I'm going alone, Gray,' she said. 
'I'll call you when I'm ready.'
 
 
 
 
 

1330
02:04:34,560 --> 02:04:35,440
CHAPTER EIGHTEEN

1331
02:04:36,320 --> 02:04:37,840
Away From It All
 

1332
02:04:40,400 --> 02:04:45,040
By 11 p.m. only four lawyers remained 
in the offices of White and Blazevich.  

1333
02:04:46,000 --> 02:04:53,520
They were Velmano, Sims Wakefield, Jarreld 
Schwabe and a retired partner named Frank Cortz.

1334
02:04:55,280 --> 02:04:59,520
Cortz finished a phone conversation 
with one of Victor Mattiece's staff.  

1335
02:05:01,920 --> 02:05:10,800
'That was Strider,' he said. 'They're in Cairo, 
in some hotel. Mattiece won't talk to us and,  

1336
02:05:11,520 --> 02:05:18,000
of course, he isn't coming back over here. 
Strider says he's behaving very strangely.  

1337
02:05:19,200 --> 02:05:24,800
They've told the boys with the guns to 
leave town immediately. The chase is over.'

1338
02:05:26,720 --> 02:05:30,240
'So what are we supposed to do?' asked Wakefield.

1339
02:05:31,120 --> 02:05:36,560
'We're on our own,' said Cortz. 
'Mattiece isn't going to help us.'

1340
02:05:38,080 --> 02:05:41,760
There was silence around the table 
as they all looked into the future.  

1341
02:05:43,040 --> 02:05:48,240
Then Velmano said, 'Grantham 
only mentioned me and Sims.  

1342
02:05:49,280 --> 02:05:56,560
You two may be OK. And I've got enough money saved 
to spend the rest of my life hiding in Europe.'

1343
02:05:58,080 --> 02:06:05,440
'It's all right for you,' Wakefield said. 'I 
can't hide. I've got a wife and six children.'

1344
02:06:06,960 --> 02:06:12,320
'I think you should go home and tell 
your wife what to expect,' Velmano said.

1345
02:06:13,040 --> 02:06:19,360
'I can't do that,' Wakefield 
said. He got up and left the room.

1346
02:06:20,880 --> 02:06:25,440
A minute later they heard the sound 
of a single gunshot from his office.

1347
02:06:28,040 --> 02:06:29,040
***

1348
02:06:29,040 --> 02:06:34,400
After eight days in the sun of the Virgin 
Islands her skin was brown enough and her  

1349
02:06:34,400 --> 02:06:40,320
hair was returning to its natural colour. 
She walked miles up and down the beaches  

1350
02:06:40,320 --> 02:06:46,000
and ate nothing except fish and fruit. 
She slept a lot the first few days.

1351
02:06:47,520 --> 02:06:51,920
She looked at her wrist and then remembered 
that her watch was in a bag somewhere.  

1352
02:06:53,040 --> 02:07:01,280
She didn't need it here. She woke with the sun and 
went to bed after dark. But now she was waiting,  

1353
02:07:02,080 --> 02:07:03,680
so she had looked at her wrist.

1354
02:07:04,960 --> 02:07:10,480
It was almost dark when the taxi stopped 
at the end of the small road. He got out,  

1355
02:07:11,200 --> 02:07:18,080
paid the driver and looked at the lights as the 
car disappeared back up the road. He had one bag.  

1356
02:07:19,440 --> 02:07:24,720
He could see a light from the house between the 
trees at the edge of the beach, and he walked  

1357
02:07:24,720 --> 02:07:33,680
towards it. He didn't know what to expect. He knew 
how he felt about her, but did she feel the same?

1358
02:07:35,520 --> 02:07:38,800
She was waiting at the back of 
the house, looking out to sea,  

1359
02:07:39,440 --> 02:07:46,240
with a drink in her hand. She smiled at him, 
put down her drink and let him come to her.

1360
02:07:47,520 --> 02:07:52,480
They kissed for a long minute. 
'You're late,' she said.

1361
02:07:53,440 --> 02:07:59,440
'This is not the easiest place to find,' 
Gray said. 'Even when you have directions.'

1362
02:08:00,960 --> 02:08:06,480
'I know,' she said. 'That's the idea. 
It's beautiful, though, isn't it?'

1363
02:08:07,520 --> 02:08:09,920
'It is. You are too.'

1364
02:08:11,280 --> 02:08:13,520
'Let's go for a walk,' she said.

1365
02:08:14,640 --> 02:08:20,000
He changed into a pair of shorts and they 
walked together on the beach, hand in hand.

1366
02:08:20,840 --> 02:08:23,520
'You left early,' she said.

1367
02:08:24,640 --> 02:08:31,040
'I got tired of it. I've written a story a day 
since the big one, and they kept wanting more.  

1368
02:08:32,160 --> 02:08:37,360
I was working eighteen hours a 
day. Yesterday I said goodbye.'

1369
02:08:38,720 --> 02:08:41,680
'I haven't seen a paper for days,' she said.

1370
02:08:42,880 --> 02:08:49,920
'Coal's finished. The President will be OK. 
I don't think he did anything really bad;  

1371
02:08:49,920 --> 02:08:56,000
he's just stupid. He won't get reelected, 
though. You read about Wakefield?'

1372
02:08:57,120 --> 02:08:59,920
'Yes, that was in the last paper I saw.'

1373
02:09:01,040 --> 02:09:05,680
'They've got Schwabe. They want 
Velmano too, but he's disappeared.  

1374
02:09:06,560 --> 02:09:11,200
Of course Mattiece is in deep trouble, 
and they're after four of his men too.'

1375
02:09:12,880 --> 02:09:18,560
They walked in silence along the beach. She put 
her arm round his waist and he pulled her closer.  

1376
02:09:20,560 --> 02:09:27,120
'I've missed you,' she said softly. 
He breathed deeply, but said nothing.  

1377
02:09:28,720 --> 02:09:31,840
'How long will you stay?' she asked.

1378
02:09:32,960 --> 02:09:39,440
'I don't know. A couple of weeks. 
Maybe a year. It depends on you.'

1379
02:09:41,440 --> 02:09:46,160
'Let's take it a month at a time. OK, Gray?'

1380
02:09:46,160 --> 02:09:49,440
'Perfect.'
 
 

1381
02:09:49,440 --> 02:09:49,972
- THE END -

